<title>REI Providers Association Bylaws</title>
</head>

<body bgcolor="ffffff">
<a href="bylaws.rtf">Download these bylaws in rich text format.</a><p>
<a href="info.html" target="_top">Return to previous page.</a><p>
<pre>
                                                Final Draft
                                             April 19, 1996

                             Bylaws

                             of the

         Real Estate Information Providers Association

                    A Nonprofit Corporation

Article I - General Provisions

1.  NAME.  The name of the corporation shall be The Real Estate
Information Providers Association (hereinafter referred to as the
"Association").  The Association is a nonprofit corporation
incorporated in the state of Virginia.

2.  LOCATION.  The principal office of the Association shall be
located in Washington, D.C. or such other place as the Board of
Directors from time to time may determine.

3.  MISSION STATEMENT.  The Real Estate Information Providers
Association is established to provide a forum for providers of
real estate information and/or information technology related to
real estate.  The Association includes all segments of the real
estate industry, including commercial and residential real
estate.  The mission of the Association shall be:

          (a)  to ensure the free and open access to public, real
          estate-related information;

          (b)  to facilitate the free and efficient flow of
          information to improve the quality of real estate
          information and, by protecting a free and efficient
          market in the flow of real estate-related information,
          ultimately to reduce the cost of real estate
          transactions to the consumer and insure fair and 
          appropriate real property valuation;

          (c)  to help ensure the responsible use and
          discrimination of real estate-related information,
          including appropriate protections for the privacy and
          accuracy of real estate-related information;

          (d)  to provide a vehicle for research and development
          of standards and priorities to further the responsible
          dissemination of data to meet the highest ethical
          standards;

          (e)  to educate public policy makers in legislative,
          administrative, regulatory and judicial branches of
          local, state and national government and the media;

          (f)  to disseminate the current trends in
          communications and the latest developments in
          information technology to its members;

          (g)  to encourage its members to know and be responsive
          to the needs and concerns of the consumers of real
          estate information products and services and to promote
          cooperation between its members and those of the real
          estate, financial services and related industries, and
          others, both directly and through other regional,
          national and international associations in matters
          involving the business and governmental affairs of the
          Association; and

          (h)  to provide members and others with opportunities
          for dialogue, education, advancement and self-
          improvement with respect to the providing of real
          estate information, through meetings, conferences,
          seminars, communications, publications, and any other
          appropriate programs and activities.


4.  RESTRICTIONS.  All policies and activities of the Association
shall be consistent with:

          (a)  procedures established by the Board of Directors;

          (b)  applicable federal, state and local antitrust,
          trade regulation and other legal requirements; and

          (c)  applicable tax-exemption requirements, including
          the requirements that the Association not be organized
          for profit and that no part of its net earnings inure
          to the benefit of any private individual.

Article II - Membership

1.  MEMBERSHIP QUALIFICATIONS - Subject to the approval of the
Board of Directors, membership in the Association shall be
available to all persons and firms actively involved in,
associated with, or having an interest in, the provision and/or
sale of real estate information or information services or other
information products.  Such approval of membership is in the sole
discretion of the Board of Directors.

2.  CLASSES OF MEMBERSHIP.  The Association shall have the
following classes of membership.

     (a)  Regular and Associate Membership; Sustaining Members.

                    (1)  Regular Membership in the Association
               shall be open to all corporations, partnerships or
               other business organizations that are engaged
               actively (as determined by the Board of Directors)
               in the provision of real estate information
               products and services, and other organizations as
               the Board from time to time may deem appropriate
               for Regular Membership.  Only one individual
               designated as the Representative of a Regular
               Member shall be entitled to vote and may be
               eligible to serve as a Director and Officer of the
               Association.  Regular Members shall inform the
               Board of Directors as to the name and title of the
               individual designated as its Representative.  Such
               Representative may cast the Regular Member's vote,
               in person or by valid proxy, at any Association
               Meeting of Members.  Representatives may
               participate fully in the business and affairs of
               the Association.

                    (2)  Associate Membership.  Any corporations,
               partnerships, associations or other business
               organizations that are not eligible to be a
               Regular Member but have a legitimate interest in
               the business of the Association, such as vendors
               selling services and products to information
               providers, may, in the sole discretion of the
               Board, be admitted to Associate Membership.  An
               Associate Member shall have no vote nor be
               eligible to serve as a Director or Officer of the
               Association.  Associate Members may participate in
               Association activities as approved by the Board.

                    (3)  Sustaining Members.  The Board of
               Directors shall have the power to designate
               certain Regular and Associate members as
               Sustaining Regular Members and Sustaining
               Associate Members in order to recognize
               outstanding contributions made by such Members to
               the work of the Association.  The designation of
               Sustaining Member shall be based on criteria
               established by the Board.  Designation of a
               Regular Member or Associate Member as Sustaining
               shall have no effect on the voting rights a Member
               otherwise possesses.

          (b)  Honorary Membership.  Special membership status as
          an Honorary Member may be conferred on individuals by
          the Board of Directors.  No dues shall be paid by
          Honorary Members, and they shall have no vote nor be
          eligible to serve as a Director or Officer of the
          Association.  They may otherwise participate in
          Association activities as approved by the Board.


3.  APPLICATIONS FOR MEMBERSHIP.  All applicants for membership
must complete, sign, and submit to the Association's principal
office, the application form provided by the Association.  All
candidates for admission to either Regular or Associate
Membership in the Association shall subscribe to and agree to be
bound by the Certificate of Incorporation, the Bylaws of the
Association, and such other terms of membership as the Board of
Directors shall determine, from time to time, and shall agree to
pay the prescribed dues and fees.

4.  ADMISSION OF NEW MEMBERS. Admission to a class of membership
in the Association shall be by a majority vote of the Board of
Directors and its decisions shall be final.

5.  RESIGNATION.  Any member may resign by filing a written
resignation with the Board of Directors; however, resignation
shall not relieve a member from liability for the full amount of
the current year's dues, as well as any additional expenses that
are accrued and unpaid as of the date of resignation.  Membership
shall not be transferable.

6.  SUSPENSION OR EXPULSION.  Any member may be suspended,
expelled, or dropped from membership for:  (a) nonpayment of dues
as provided in Article III, Section 2, or (b) other good cause by
a two-thirds vote of the entire Board of Directors.  Any member
proposed for suspension or expulsion for any reason, other than
delinquency in the payment of dues, shall be given advance
written notice, including the reason for the proposed action.
The member shall then be given an opportunity to contest the
proposed action in writing, or in person, before the Board of
Directors.  Final written notice of the Board's decision will be
given to the member.

Article III - Dues

1.  DUES AND FEES.  The Board has the power to establish dues as
a condition of membership for each class of membership in the
Association.  The Board also shall have the power to establish
fees for other services or products supplied by the Association.
The Board shall have the sole responsibility for setting the
amount and time for payment of any dues and fees.

2.  DELINQUENCY.  Any member of the Association who is delinquent
in dues or fees for a period of ninety (90) days shall be
notified of the delinquency and suspended from membership.  If
dues are not paid within the succeeding thirty (30) days, the
delinquent member shall forfeit all rights and privileges of
membership, including the rights to attend any Meeting of the
Association and to vote on any Association matter, and shall be
dropped from membership.

3.  REFUNDS.  No dues or fees will be refunded, except in
circumstances determined by the Board of Directors.

Article IV - Board of Directors

1.  DIRECTORS.  The governing body of the Association shall be
the Board of Directors, which shall consist of persons who are
Representatives and are elected by and from the Regular Members
and Associate Members.  No more than one Director shall be from a
single Regular or Associate Member at a given time.  If a person
ceases to be a Representative, he/she shall automatically cease
to be eligible to continue to serve as a Director.

2.  DUTIES.  The Board of Directors shall have authority and
shall be responsible for the supervision, control and direction
of the Association.

3.  ELECTION AND TERM OF DIRECTORS.  Directors shall be elected
at the Association's Annual Meeting by a vote of the
Representatives of the Regular Members.  Each year a number of
Directors shall be elected sufficient to have nine (9) Directors
in office.  The Term of a Director shall be three years, and
shall begin immediately after the Business Meeting of the Annual
Meeting at which election takes place, or in the case of a
special election created by a vacancy, immediately upon election.
Directors may serve not more than two full consecutive terms.

4.  INITIAL BOARD AND STAGGERED TERMS.  Terms of Directors will
be staggered.  The initial Board will be composed of three
Directors having a three-year term, three Directors having a two-
year term, and three Directors having a one-year term.  Service
for a Directorship term of less than the full three year's
duration shall not count towards the two consecutive terms limit
of Article IV.A.3.

5.  VACANCIES.  If a vacancy occurs on the Board of Directors for
any reason other than the expiration of a Director's full term,
the vacancy shall be filled by a vote of the Board of Directors
until the next Annual Meeting.

6.  MEETINGS.  The Board of Directors shall have regularly
scheduled Meetings at least annually at whatever time and place
it selects.  The presence of a majority of Directors shall
constitute a quorum sufficient for a Meeting.  A majority of
Directors at a Meeting where a quorum is present may make
decisions except where some other number is required by law or by
these Bylaws.  Proxy voting by the Directors shall not be
permitted.  Some or all of the Directors may participate in a
Meeting either in person or by conference telephone or other
means by which all of the Directors can hear one another or
otherwise receive the views of the other Directors participating
in the Meeting.  Presence at a Meeting within the meaning of this
Article includes physical presence at the Meeting site,
participation via telephone call in the Meeting, or participation
via any other electronic means which permits the Directors to
communicate with one another and receive the views of all
Directors participating in the Meeting, such as via on-line
service, unless otherwise required by law.

7.  REMOVAL.  A Director may be removed for good cause at any
time by a two-thirds vote of the Board of Directors.  In
addition, a Director who fails to be present at four consecutive
regularly scheduled Board Meetings, without leave of the
Chairperson, shall automatically be deemed to have resigned,
provided that for good cause shown the Board may in its
discretion immediately reinstate such Director for the remainder
of his/her Term.

8.  COMPENSATION.  Directors shall serve without compensation for
their services.  Directors may be reimbursed for reasonable
travel expenses related to work for the Association and incurred
at the direction of the Board of Directors.

Article V - Officers

1.  OFFICERS.  The Officers of the Association shall be a
President, President-Elect, Immediate Past President, Treasurer,
Secretary, and Membership Director.  All officers except the
Treasurer and Secretary must be current members of the Board of
Directors.  The Treasurer and Secretary must be Representatives
of Regular Members or Representatives of Associate Members in
good standing, but neither the Treasurer nor the Secretary need
be a Director.  Officers shall be elected by the Board except for
the Treasurer and the Secretary who shall be appointed by the
President-Elect at the beginning of his term as President to
serve during his/her Term as President, subject to the advice and
consent of the Board of Directors.  The Term of an Officer shall
be one year.

2.  QUALIFICATIONS.  Officers shall be Representatives of Regular
Members of the Association who are currently Directors, except
the Treasurer and Secretary.  If an Officer ceases to be a
Director, or ceases to be a Representative of a Regular Member,
he/she shall automatically cease to be eligible to continue to
serve as an Officer.  The President-Elect may not be elected
unless he/she has served as a Director during the full year
immediately preceding such election, except for the initial year
of operation of the Association.

3.  DUTIES.

     (a)  Powers and duties of the President.  The President
shall:

                    (1)  Preside at any Meeting of the whole
               Association;

                    (2)  Preside at all Meetings of the Board of
               Directors and act as Chairperson of the Board;

                    (3)  As provided in Article VIII, appoint
               committees and task forces; and

                    (4)  Perform such other administrative duties
               as from time to time may be required.

     The President may sign and execute any instrument in the
     name of the Association when authorized to do so by the
     Board of Directors.

          (b)  Powers and duties of the President-Elect.  The
          President-Elect shall:

                    (1)  Assist the President in any and all of
               his powers and duties;

                    (2)  Act as President, if the President is
               unable or unavailable to fulfill his duties;

                    (3)  Assist the President in hosting and
               planning the Meetings of the Association,
               including the Annual Meeting; and

                    (4)  Perform such other administrative duties
               as from time to time may be required.

     The President-Elect may sign and execute any instrument in
     the name of the Association when authorized to do so by the
     Board of Directors.

          (c)  Powers and duties of the Immediate Past President.
          The Immediate Past President shall:

                    (1)  Perform such duties as from time to time
               may be delegated to him by the Board of Directors.

                    (2)  He/she may act as President, if both the
               President and the President-Elect are unable to
               attend a Meeting, and they so consent; and

                    (3)  Along with the President and the
               Executive Director, he will oversee the
               Association's government relations activities by
               serving as liaison to the Government Relations
               Committee.

          (d)  Powers and duties of the Treasurer.  The Treasurer
          shall:

                    (1)  Perform such duties as from time to time
               may be delegated to him by the Board of Directors.
               He/she may sign and execute any instrument in the
               name of the Association when authorized by the
               President;

                    (2)  Along with the Executive Director,
               review and render a statement of accounts to the
               Board of Directors in accordance with these
               Bylaws; and

                    (3)  At all reasonable times exhibit the
               books of account of the Association to the members
               of the Association upon request.

     The Board of Directors may require that the Treasurer post a
     bond for the faithful performance of his duties, the cost of
     such bond for the faithful performance of his duties to be
     borne by the Association.

     (e)  Powers and duties of the Secretary.  The Secretary
shall:

                    (1)  Perform such duties as from time to time
               may be delegated to him by the Board of Directors.
               He/she shall be responsible for the preparation
               and circulation of the agenda for each Meeting of
               the Board of Directors;

                    (2)  Be responsible for the preparation of
               minutes of all Meetings of the Board of Directors;

                    (3)  Be otherwise responsible for overseeing
               the observance of corporate formalities and all
               legal compliance of the Association; and

                    (4)  Conduct elections of the Association.

          (f)  Membership Director.  The Membership Director
          shall:

                    (1)  Perform such duties as from time to time
               may be delegated to him/her by the Board of
               Directors;

                    (2)  Be responsible for creating and
               maintaining a strong membership base for the
               Association; and

                    (3)  Chair the Membership Committee of the
               Association.

4.  INITIAL OFFICERS.  At the start-up of the Association, the
initial officers shall be drawn from the initial Board of
Directors.

5.  VACANCIES.  If a vacancy occurs among the Officers for any
reason, then the vacancy may be filled by the Board of Directors.

6.  REMOVAL.  An Officer may be removed for good cause at any
time by a two-thirds vote of the Board of Directors.  In
addition, an Officer who fails to be present at two consecutive
regularly scheduled Board Meetings without leave of the
Chairperson shall automatically be deemed to have resigned,
provided that for good cause shown the Board may in its
discretion immediately reinstate such Officer for the remainder
of his/her Term.

7.  COMPENSATION.  Officers shall serve without compensation for
their services.  Officers may be reimbursed for reasonable travel
expenses related to work for the Association.

Article VI - Executive Director

The Executive Director shall be an individual or an organization
selected by the Board.  The Executive Director shall serve at the
pleasure of the Board, subject to any contractual agreement.  The
Executive Director shall have such powers and obligations, and
perform such functions, and be subject to such policies and
limitations as may be prescribed by the Board.  The Board shall
review the performance of the Executive Director annually, or at
such other interval of time the Board shall select.  The powers
and duties of the Executive Director shall include:

          (a)  Responsibility for the day-to-day operations of
          the Association and general and active supervision of
          the business of the Association, subject to the control
          of the Board of Directors;

          (b)  Implementing the orders and resolutions of the
          Board of Directors;

          (c)  Reporting from time to time to the Board of
          Directors on all matters within his/her knowledge which
          the interest of the Association may require to be
          brought to the notice of the Board of Directors;

          (d)  Operating a national office for the Association
          and contract for necessary and appropriate goods and
          services in this regard, provided that purchases,
          contracts, leases, or other financial commitments
          obligating the Association to total payments in excess
          of $2,500 shall require cosignature of the President,
          or other written and signed authorization of the
          President, unless the total payments are in excess of
          $25,000, in which case the matter shall first be
          brought to the Board of Directors for approval;

          (e)  Maintaining all membership and Association
          corporate records, membership renewals, mailing lists
          and general files;

          (f)  Assisting the Secretary by conducting elections
          and preparing minutes of all Meetings of the Board of
          Directors and such other resolutions and reports as
          required;

          (g)  Providing general advice and guidance to the Board
          of Directors and the officers of the Association and
          consulting with them regarding problems, concerns and
          activities of the Association;

          (h)  Promoting growth in the membership of the
          Association, including the development of prospect
          lists;

          (i)  Handling communications from and to members of the
          Association, and from the Association to the public at
          large;

          (j)  Coordinating and publishing all Association
          publications, including electronic publications such as
          the Association's site on the World Wide Web;

          (k)  Conducting the Association's Meetings and
          conferences;

          (l)  Performing all the financial duties incident to
          the Association, subject to the control of the Board of
          Directors, including maintenance of account and dues
          records, preparation of balance sheets and dues
          updates, arrangement for an annual review or audit at
          the Association's expense, preparation of a budget and
          receipt, deposit and disbursement of monies;

          (m)  Entering regularly in books to be kept by him/her
          for that purpose full and accurate account of all
          monies received and paid him/her on account of the
          Association;

          (n)  Performing such other duties as may be assigned to
          him/her from time to time by the Board of Directors.
          The Executive Director may sign and execute any
          instrument in the name of the Association when
          authorized to do so by the Board of Directors.

     The Board of Directors may require that the Executive
     Director post a bond for faithful performance of his duties,
     the cost of such a bond to be borne by the Association.

Article VII - Meetings

1.  ANNUAL MEMBERSHIP MEETING.  The Association shall hold an
Annual Meeting at the place and time and on the date that the
Board of Directors determines.

2.  SPECIAL MEETINGS.  Special Meetings of the Association may be
called by the Board of Directors at any time.

3.  NOTICE.  The Board of Directors shall give Association
members not less than fifteen (15) days written notice of all
annual and special Meetings of Members.  The notice shall include
a general description of the business to be discussed.

4.  VOTING.  A presence of thirty percent of the Representatives
of the Regular Members shall constitute a quorum.  A majority of
such Representatives at a Meeting where a quorum is present may
make decisions, except where some other number is required by law
or by these Bylaws.  Each Regular Member shall be entitled to one
vote to be cast by its Representative.  A Regular Member may
designate by written proxy a person from the same organization to
vote on its behalf in lieu of its usual Representative, if the
Representative will be absent.  If requested, the written proxy
must be presented at the Meeting or else no one except the
Representative will be allowed to vote.

Article VIII - Other Provisions

1.  COMMITTEES AND TASK FORCES.  The Board of Directors may
delegate to an Executive Committee, comprised of the Officers of
the Association, such specific duties and responsibilities as the
Board of Directors may from time to time determine, provided that
the Executive Committee shall report matters as appropriate to
the full Board, and the full Board shall at all times retain
general and overall responsibility for conducting the affairs of
the Association.  The President, with the approval of the Board
of Directors, may appoint other committees and task forces, to
which particular duties and responsibilities may be delegated.
No person may serve on a Committee unless he/she is a Member in
good standing.  No person may continue as a Committee Member if
he/she misses two consecutive Meetings of such Committee unless,
for good cause, a majority of such Committee excuses such
absence.  In addition to the Board of Directors, the Association
shall have five permanent committees -- the Government Relations
Committee, the Technology Committee, the Membership Committee,
the Standards Committee, and the Industry Promotion and
Communications Committee.

          (a)  The Government Relations Committee will monitor
          developments in state and federal courts, local, state
          and federal litigation and administrative rule makings
          or other proceedings that affect the operations of the
          Industry, and advise the Association with respect to
          the opportunities to educate public policymakers.  The
          Government Relations Committee will have the
          responsibility for developing liaisons with other trade
          associations and industry groups on issues of interest
          to the Association's members.

          (b)  The Technology Committee shall monitor technology
          developments in the real estate information industry,
          including related developments in the communications
          and computer industry, and advise the Association with
          respect to the technical issues confronting the
          Industry.

          (c)  The Membership Committee shall assist the
          President with creating and maintaining a strong
          membership base of the Association and conduct
          educational outreach efforts to develop awareness about
          the Association among real estate information firms,
          professionals, associations, vendors, customers, and
          related technology companies.

          (d)  The Standards Committee shall monitor
          developments in the industry and consider various data
          standards that could further the fair and efficient
          dissemination of real estate information.

          (e)  The Industry Promotion and Communications
          Committee shall assist the Association in developing
          and implementing Association strategy to promote the
          responsible use and dissemination of real estate
          information products and services.  The Committee will
          have the responsibility to communicate the
          Association's activities among its Members and to the
          public at large.

Ad hoc committees may be formed from time to time by the Board of
Directors to carry out special projects and assignments.

2.  RULES.  The Board of Directors may establish rules that are
consistent with these Bylaws for the policies, procedures and
programs of the Association.

Article IX - Indemnification

1.  Directors & Officers

          (a)  The Association shall, to the fullest extent now
          or hereafter permitted by law, indemnify any person who
          was or is a party, or is threatened to be made a party
          to any threatened, pending or completed action, suit or
          proceeding, whether civil, criminal, administrative or
          investigative (other than an action by or in the right
          of the Association) by reason of the fact that such
          person is or was a Director or Officer of the
          Association, a Chair, Vice-Chair or member of any
          Committee or Task Force of the Association, or an
          employee or other agent of the Association or of any
          other organization served by him in any capacity at the
          request of the Association against expenses (including
          attorneys' fees) judgments, fines, amounts paid in
          settlement, actually and reasonably incurred by such
          person in connection with such action, suit or
          proceeding, if he/she acted in good faith and in a
          manner he/she reasonably believed to be in, or not
          opposed to, the best interest of the Association, and,
          with respect to any criminal action or proceeding,
          he/she had no reasonable cause to believe that his/her
          conduct was unlawful.  The termination of any action,
          suit or proceeding by judgment, order, settlement,
          conviction, or upon a plea of nolo contendere or its
          equivalent, shall not, of itself, create a presumption
          that the person did not act in good faith and in a
          manner which he/she reasonably believed to be in, or
          not opposed to, the best interests of the Association,
          and, with respect to the criminal action or proceeding,
          had no reasonable cause to believe that his/her conduct
          was unlawful.

          (b)  The Association shall indemnify any person who was
          or is a party, or is threatened to be made a party, to
          any threatened, pending or completed action, suit or
          proceeding by or in the right of the Association to
          procure a judgment in its favor by reason of the fact
          that he/she is or was a Director or Officer of the
          Association, or a Chair, Vice-Chair, or member of any
          Committee or Task Force of the Association, or an
          employee or other agent of the Association or of any
          other organization served by him in any capacity at the
          request of the Association against expenses (including
          attorneys' fees) actually and reasonably incurred by
          him/her in connection with the defense or settlement of
          such action or suit, if he/she acted in good faith and
          in a manner he/she reasonably believed to be in, or not
          opposed to, the best interest of the Association.  No
          indemnification shall be made in respect of any claim,
          issue or matter as to which such person shall have been
          adjudged to be liable for negligence or misconduct in
          the performance of his/her duty to the Association,
          unless, and only to the extent that, a court in which
          action or suit was brought shall determine upon
          application that, despite the adjudication of
          liability, but in view of all the circumstances of the
          case, such person is fairly and reasonably entitled to
          indemnity for such expenses.

          (c)  To the extent that any person referred to in
          subparagraphs (a) and (b) of this paragraph 1 has been
          successful on the merits or otherwise in defense of any
          action, suit or proceeding referred to therein or in
          defense of any claim, issue or matter therein, he/she
          shall be indemnified against expenses (including
          attorneys' fees) actually and reasonably incurred by
          him/her in connection therewith.

          (d)  Any indemnification under subparagraphs (a) and
          (b) of this paragraph 1 (unless ordered by a court)
          shall be made by the Association only as authorized in
          the specific case upon a determination that
          indemnification of the person is proper in the
          circumstances because he/she has met the applicable
          standard of conduct set forth in subparagraphs (a) and
          (b) of this paragraph 1.  Such determination shall be
          made (i) by the Board of Directors by a majority vote
          of a quorum consisting of Directors who were not
          parties to such action, suit or proceedings, or (ii) if
          such a quorum is not obtainable, or, even if
          obtainable, a quorum of disinterested Directors so
          directs, by independent legal counsel in a written
          opinion, or (iii) if neither of the preceding actions
          occurs, by a majority vote of the Representatives of
          Regular Members.

          (e)  Expenses incurred in defending a civil or criminal
          action, suit or proceeding may be paid by the
          Association in advance of the final disposition of such
          action, suit or proceeding if the Board so authorizes
          in light of all the circumstances, and upon receipt of
          an undertaking by or on behalf of the Director or
          Officer by or on behalf of whom such expenses are
          incurred to repay such amount unless it shall
          ultimately be determined that he/she is entitled to be
          indemnified by the Association as provided in this
          paragraph 1.

          (f)  The indemnification provided by this paragraph 1
          shall not be deemed to preclude any other rights to
          which a person seeking indemnification may be entitled
          under any statute, bylaw, agreement, vote of members of
          disinterested Directors or otherwise, both as to action
          in his/her official capacity and as to action in
          another capacity while holding such office, and shall
          continue as to a person who has ceased to be a Director
          or Officer, and shall inure to the benefit of the
          heirs, executors and administrators of such person.

          (g)  The Association shall have power to purchase and
          maintain insurance covering the Association and any
          person who is or was a Director, Officer, employee,
          agent or Chair, Vice-Chair, or member of a Committee,
          Task Force or similar group of the Association, against
          liability asserted against such persons and incurred in
          any such capacity, or arising out of his/her status as
          such, whether or not the Association would have the
          power to indemnify him/her against such liability under
          the provisions of this paragraph 1.

2.  EMPLOYEES AND AGENTS.  The Board of Directors may, by
resolution, extend prospectively or retrospectively the
indemnification provisions of the foregoing paragraph 1 to any
person, business, entity, or organization who was or is a party
or is threatened to be made party to any threatened, pending or
completed action, suit or proceeding by reason of the fact that
he/she is or was an employee, agent, or other officially
designated representative of the Association.

Article X - Antitrust Compliance

It is the policy of the Association to comply fully with all
applicable laws, including the antitrust laws, and accordingly,
all activities of the Association shall be conducted in
accordance with its Antitrust Compliance Guidelines, as they from
time to time may be adopted or modified by the Board of
Directors.

Article XI - Member Representations

No member of the Association is authorized to speak or take
action on behalf of the Association without the prior specific
authorization of the Board of Directors.  In addition, no member
is authorized to use the name or logo of the Association for
conducting its non-Association business in any manner that
suggests or reasonably may be interpreted to imply the approval
by the Association, rather than or in addition to mere members in
the Association.

Article XII - Books and Records

The Association shall keep correct and complete books and records
of account and shall also keep minutes of the proceedings of its
members, Board of Directors, and committees having any of the
authority of the Board of Directors, and shall keep at the
registered or principal office a record giving the names and
addresses of the members entitled to vote.  All books and records
of the Association, except for records reflecting internal
personnel matters, executive session matters, litigation and
claim-related matters, or other matters properly kept
confidential, may be inspected by any member, or his agent or
attorney, for any proper purpose, at any reasonable time.

Article XIII - Arbitration

Grievances of a Regular Member, Associate Member, or Honorary
Member against the Association first shall be presented to the
Board of Directors and Executive Director.  If the grievance is
unresolved by the Board of Directors and Executive Director, then
Regular Members, Associate Members and Honorary Members agree to
waive trial by jury in favor of arbitration of any grievance
against the Association or against a Member of the Association in
the course of Association work or against an employee or agent of
the Association at a site selected by the Board of Directors in
the Washington, D.C. metropolitan area, or at such alternative
site as is agreeable to the Board of Directors of the
Association.  Such arbitration shall be conducted under the rules
of the American Arbitration Association.

Article XIV - Fiscal Year

The fiscal year of the Association shall be the calendar year.

Article XV - Amendments

The Bylaws may be amended by vote of two-thirds of the entire
Board of Directors of the Association at a Meeting held after at
least two weeks written notice shall have been sent to the Board
of Directors stating the substance of the proposed amendment.

Article XVI - Dissolution

The Association may be dissolved upon the affirmative vote of
three-quarters of the entire Board of Directors.  In the event of
such dissolution, the remaining assets of the Association shall
be applied and distributed pursuant to Virginia law.

Adopted by the Chartering Committee,          1996
</pre>
</body>
</html>
