<HEAD>
<TITLE>Access Issues -- Our Philosophy-- REIPA</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor=ffffff>
<center><u>
<P><b><font size=+1>DRAFT 2.0 </P>
<P>Principles of Government Sourced Data, </P>
<P>Commercial Dissemination and Responsible Information Handling</font></b></P>
<P>an Industry Whitepaper Prepared by:  </P>
<P>Real Estate Information Providers Association's (REIPA)</P>
<P>Government Affairs Committee</P>
</u>
<P>Rufus Lusk, Chair</P>
<P>November 15, 1996</P>
</center>

<a href="#i">
<P><B><I><u>I. The Public Record Has a Long and Important History in Promoting
American Democracy and Commerce 
</a>

<hr width=70%>
<a href="#ii">
<P>II. Better Information Means Fairer Markets 
</a>

<hr width=70%>
<a href="#iii">
<P>III.  Better Real Estate Information is Critical to the Real Estate Financing, Sales and Leasing Markets of Tomorrow
</a>

<hr width=70%>
<a href="#iv">
<P>IV. The Role of Private Firms 
</a>

<hr width=70%>
<a href="#v">
<P>V. Public Records and the Marketplace of Ideas 
</a>

<hr width=70%>
<a href="#vi">
<P>VI. Publicly Disseminated Real Estate Information Helps Safeguard the Public by Deterring Fraud
</a>

<hr width=70%>
<a href="#vii">
<P>VII. The Transition to an Information Age Refocuses the Issues 
</a>

<hr width=70%>
<a href="#viii">
<P>VIII. Not All Government Collected Information is Public Record 
</a>

<hr width=70%>
<a href="#ix">
<P>IX. Government Sourced Data  Creates  Societal Wealth and Increased
Tax Revenues 
</a>

<hr width=70%>
<a href="#x">
<P>X. The REI Providers Association
</a>

<hr width=70%>
<a href="#xi">
<P>XI. Responsible Information  Handling 
</a>

<hr width=70%>
<a href="#xii">
<P>XII. REIPA's Fair Information Values (FIV): 
</a>

<hr width=70%>
<a href="#xiii">
<P>XIII. REIPA's Fair Information Practices (FIP): 
</a>

<hr width=70%>
<a href="#xiv">
<P>XIV. Access to Publicly Sourced Real Estate Data Should be
Unrestricted and at the Cost of Reproduction 
</a>

<hr width=70%>
<a href="#xv">
<P>XV. Government Information Dissemination Principles
</a>

<hr width=70%>
<a href="#xvi">
<p>XVI. Ongoing Study 					  </I></B></u>
</a>

<hr width=70%>
<b><u>
<a name="i"></a>
<P>I. The Public Record Has a Long and Important History in Promoting American
Democracy and Commerce	
</b></u>
<P>Since the colonization of the New World in the 17th century, open public
records have been a basic cornerstone of American commerce and society.  In
going from the Old World of privilege for some to the New World of opportunity
for all, there was a paradigm shift in the way that government data was viewed. 
The public record evolved from being the property of a certain class to the
possession of all.  This  important and fundamental American tradition, rooted
in the writings of great democratic political philosophers such as John Locke, 
was first practiced in Colonial New England, and later  affirmed by the
country's Founders.  They believed that information, appropriately and
responsibly used,  should promote democracy, by increasing the nature and extent
of citizen knowledge and participation in governmental decisions, the economy,
and politics, both at the national and local levels.  This viewpoint flowed from
a profound, revolutionary idea:  government belongs to the public, not to a
sovereign.</P>
<P>Government agencies collect information while recording property ownership
and transfers, assessing taxes, setting zoning, and approving permits.  This
information has always been collected, not only to allow the government to do
its specific work, but also with the goal of public dissemination.  Open
ownership laws and public review examination of the ownership, sale and transfer
of real estate have been an established part of public policy since the earliest
days of our democracy.  Moreover it was always felt that if the records were
kept restricted and secret that there would be many more opportunities for
corruption, secret dealings, and dishonest and unfair property accumulation. 
All one has to do is open the newspaper to see the value of public real estate
data being  open to the public.  Virtually every day a reporter writes a story
about the prosecutor who attacks questionable associations involving public
officials, a political campaign's review of the opponent's dealings, or the
newspaper's own investigation of a public official's financial dealings.</P>
<p>
<a name="ii"></a>
<b><u>II. Better Information Means Fairer Markets</H1>
</b></u>
<P>The fact that reliable information was available, from  reputable objective
sources, meant that commercial markets could develop where all parties had an
equal and  fair advantage in transactions.  The openness of the early public
record, along with its purpose of serving the greater good for the entire
society, is the genesis of the information resources that have fueled the growth
of our consumer based economy today.  The fact that information is readily
available, accurate, comprehensive and timely creates confidence in markets,
whether it be the stock market, the crop futures market or the real estate
market.  Good information translates into vibrant, fair markets; incomplete or
misleading or limited information gives unfair advantage to one particular group
to the disadvantage of others. In short bad information promotes inefficient,
unfair markets.  Our democratic American tradition has always sided with widely
disseminated information, to the benefit of all.</P>
<P>Unrestricted information flow protects markets.  The experience in other
industries is instructive. The world's largest equities markets are located in
the United States.  After the October, 1987 stock market crash, many observers
believed that the average individual stock market investor would be scared off. 
Instead the last ten years have seen an enormous flow of individual investor
dollars back to Wall Street equities.  The number of stock and bond mutual funds
has grown from 1,000 to over 7,000.  Consumers have undoubtedly been well served
by the growth of Lipper Analytical Services, Morningstar publications and
various other stock market newsletters and business journals.  Publicly
available data -- objective, timely, and comprehensive -- on mutual funds and
fund mangers performance has protected and greatly benefited consumers.  With
this knowledge and confidence the flow of investment dollars has created a much
larger equities market.(and paid for a lot of retirements and college
tuitions!). Investors have been able to make intelligent decisions based on good
data.</P>
<p>
<a name="iii"></a>
<b><u>
III. Better Real Estate Information is Critical to the Real Estate Financing, Sales and Leasing Markets of Tomorrow</b></u>
<p>
   The availability of reliable information  from  reputable, objective sou
rces, allowed the development of  commercial markets where all parties had an eq
ual and  fair advantage in transactions.  The openness of the early public recor
ds, in accordance with the established goal of serving the greater good of the e
ntire society, was an essential cornerstone in supporting the foundation of the
information resources that have fueled the growth of our consumer-based economy.
<p>
  The fact that information is readily available, accurate, comprehensive and timely creates confidence in markets, whether it be the stock market, the crop futures market, or the real estate market.  Quality information translates into  fair market vibrancy; substandard or limited information gives unfair advantage toone particular group to the disadvantage of others. In substandard  information tends to promote substandard market performance.  Our democratic American tradition has historically supported policies and programs which foster the broad-based dissemination of information, for  the benefit of all who properly apply it.  
The availability of reliable information  from  reputable, objective sources, allowed the development of  commercial markets where all parties had an equal and  fair advantage in transactions.  The openness of the early public records, in accordance with the established goal of serving the greater good of the entire society, was an essential cornerstone in supporting the foundation of the information resources that have fueled the growth of our consumer-based economy.
<p>
        Unrestricted information flow protects markets.  The experience in other industries is instructive. The world's largest equities markets are located in the United States.  After the October, 1987 stock market crash, many observers believed that the average individual stock market investor would be scared off.  Instead the last ten years have seen an enormous flow of individual investor dollars back to Wall Street equities.  The number of stock and bond mutual funds has grown from 1,000 to over 7,000.  Consumers have undoubtedly been well served by the growth of Lipper Analytical Services, Morningstar publications and various
 other stock market newsletters and business journals.  Publicly available data
-- objective, timely, and comprehensive -- on mutual funds and fund mangers performance has protected and greatly benefited consumers.  With this knowledge and
confidence the flow of investment dollars has created a much larger equities market (and paid for a lot of retirements and college tuitions!). Investors have been able to make intelligent decisions based on good data.

<p>
<a name="iv"></a>
<b><u>IV. The Role of Private Firms</H1>
</b></u><P>As private real estate information database companies developed in the 20th
century they have increasingly taken the burden off of the shoulders of local
government officials by publishing public record data from many government
agencies in hard-copy, on-line, microfiche and cd-rom media.   This has not only
reduced the costs of government by transferring the dissemination task to the
private sector but it has also provided more choice in the marketplace as a
number of firms competed to add value to the raw government data.  Today by and
large, the real estate marketplace looks to private sector information companies
to provide the tools and services that allow market value to be determined,
title condition to be analyzed, financing risks computed,  in short to
facilitate real property commerce.</P>
<p>
<a name="v"></a>
<b><u>V. Public Records and the Marketplace of Ideas</H1>
</b></u><P>After the Constitution was ratified by the thirteen original states, the
Founding Fathers drafted and the original American states adopted a Bill of
Rights to ensure the protection of fundamental freedoms.  The First of Ten
Amendments to the US Constitution guaranteed the right to free speech and
expression.  Having escaped persecution and oppression of a tyrannical monarch,
the Founding Fathers saw the value of a printing press to check government
tyranny.</P>
<P>Public records are not an exception to this fundamental core American
respect for and protection of free speech.  Access to public records serves the
same function.  Access to public records can directly protect consumers against
improper tax assessments and tax practices.  Access to public records can also
help protect buyers and sellers of property from unscrupulous operators.</P>
<p>
<a name="vi"></a>
<b><u>VI. Publicly Disseminated Real Estate Information Helps Safeguard the Public by
Deterring Fraud
</u></b>
<p>
        While Willie Sutton may have specialized in robbing banks because that was where the money was a half century ago, many unscrupulous individuals specialize in varieties of real estate fraud today.  Because of the large amounts of cash involved, the large number of people involved in the transaction and its complicated nature, and the widely dispersed ownership of real estate, there are abundant opportunites for fraud.  Fraud may be of the everyday garden variety where an elderly or unsophisticated seller is not provided full disclosure of relevant market trends and statistics or it may be of the more  nuanced type where fraudelent deeds of trust and sale are recorded on a property without the owner's consent.  In any case local, state, and federal law enforcement officials depend to a great degree on information from REIPA members for accurating reporting on real estate market events with the goal of bringing criminal fraud to light and protecting the consumer. Further restrcting access to the public records would just abet those perpetrators of fraud who already prey to easily on the unsuspecting.
<p>

<a name="vii"></a>
<p><b><u>VII. The Transition to an Information Age Refocuses the Issues</H1>
</b></u><P>The transition from an industrial to an information based economy has
refocused attention on the nature and purpose of public records and government
sourced information.  Information collected by the government when used wisely
creates real value for individuals and generates additional wealth for our
society.  At the same time we recognize that information used maliciously has
the potential to harm individuals.  We therefore need to seek appropriate
balances between the open use of information that has fueled the growth of our
economy along with the awareness that information may be used in a harmful way,
and devise and monitor appropriate safeguards.</P>
<P>Unfortunately  the unfolding democratic promises and practices of the
information age are under unremitting attacks in some quarters by government
bodies that seek to control and even severely limit access to the public's real
estate data in a number of ways.  These controlling efforts involve some of the
following: limiting access to  publicly sourced data, only releasing certain
pieces of it, charging exorbitantly for it,  giving exclusives to one party, and
claiming copyrights and demanding royalties.  All of these government efforts
result in the dissemination of real estate public record being limited and the
public's right to know impeded.  The real loser here is the public who will have
less data, and at a lower quality, when making decisions on buying, selling, and
financing real estate.  This means the public will be getting less and paying
more.  It is a profound threat to the health of real estate markets.</P>
<a name="viii"></a>
<p><b><u>VIII. Not All Government Collected Information is Public Record</H1>
</b></u><P>Governments, at the state, county,  and federal levels, collect lots of
information in fulfilling their myriad essential public purposes.  Information
is collected for school  records, professional licensing, taxing and recording
real property, to mention only a few purposes.  In some cases, the public
purpose for collecting information has historically included dissemination to
the public.  Real estate data fall into this class.  We would not have safe and
liquid real estate markets without a public real estate record built with public
dissemination in mind.  Moreover, those states and counties that are more open
in their release of real estate data  have stronger markets, more efficient
markets, more consumer oriented markets (all other things being equal) than
those areas which are data restrictive.  Quite simply, bad or non-existent
information leads to higher costs and bad decisions.</P>
<P>Other government data sets are collected without general public
dissemination being part of the public purpose for collection.  Medicaid or IRS
records are an example.  Still other records create real societal value when
disclosed, such as motor vehicle records, but were originally not collected with
dissemination in mind.</P>
<a name="ix"></a>
<P><b><u>IX. Government Sourced Data  Creates  Societal Wealth and Increased Tax
Revenues</b></u></P>
<P>The information base built by government dissemination of public records and
other private data sets is a basic infrastructure of our modern consumer
economy, just as canals were in the 19th century and roads have been in the 20th
century.  Moreover, they are an increasingly important part of the information
age infrastructure of the 21st century.  Every dollar invested by the government
in data sets that are shared with the public multiplies in employment in the
private sector, economic growth and tax revenue.  It is in the society's
interest for government to encourage and facilitate a vibrant and healthy
information industry, where the private sector is investing in new information
applications, and where no government agency or single private enterprise is
given a monopolistic advantage. </P>
<P>We advocate dissemination of government sourced data by commercial firms
committed to  Fair Information Values (FIV) and Practices (FIP).  REIPA believes
that information collected by government should be open and available unless
there is evidence that providing information to the public will harm individuals
 Furthermore, and just as important, REIPA believes that information disclosure
practices should be disclosed to the public when information is collected by the
government.  Government should also allow consumers to opt-out of the marketing
use of information, and should give other options where appropriate.</P>
<P>In a free and open society our opportunity to utilize the public record for
commercial purposes is balanced by our obligation to do this in a highly
responsible manner.  Our consumer society, marked by a high degree of personal
initiative, freedom and choice is based on consumer information. To this end we
not only assert the freedom of private firms to disseminate data, but also hold
up codes of responsible behavior for the information age. We recognize and
affirm that freedom implies responsibility.</P>
<a name="x"></a>
<b><u>X. The REI Providers Association</u></b>
<p>
        The REI Providers Association advocates dissemination of government sourced data by an information servicing industry which is committed to  Fair Information Values (FIV) and Practices (FIP).  REIPA believes that information collected by government should be open and available unless there is evidence that providing certain information sets to the public will harm, endanger or disadvantage individuals  Furthermore, and just as importantly, REIPA believes that information dissemination policies, practices and procedures should be disclosed to the public when information is collected by the government.  Agencies  should also allow consumers to opt-out of the marketing use of information, as is currently being introduced in the states in response to the Federal Drivers Privacy Protection Act (DPPA) of 1994.
<p>
        In a free and open society, our opportunity to utilize the public record for commercial purposes must be  balanced by our obligation to do this in a highly responsible manner.  Our service-oriented  society, marked by a high degree of personal initiative and  freedom to achieve limited only by one's abilities, is fueled by consumer information. To sustain long-lasting business success we must not only assert our unalienable rights to access and use of public data but also  be ever-mindful of our social obligations for responsible information handling. We recognize and affirm that freedom implies responsibility.  Moreover, the efforts required to maintain this ethical commitment should not be underestimated, because as the technological ability to create, commingle, and broadcast ever-enhanced strains of information continually expands, so do our moral obligations.
<p>



<a name="xi"></a>
<P><b><u>XI. Responsible Information  Handling </b></u></H1>
<P>REIPA members commit to and practice the highest level of responsible data
handling.  At REIPA we build services based on information that pertains to
millions of real estate parcels and their owners.  Accordingly, our members'
services are informed by REIPA's Fair Information Values (FIV) and Fair
Information Practices (FIP), which constitute rigorous self-regulation.</P>
<a name="xii"></a>
<p><b><u>XII. REIPA's Fair Information Values (FIV):</b></u>
<P>1)Partnership:We partner with customers to meet legitimate business needs.</P>
<P>2)Fairness:   We strive to meet consumer expectations about accuracy and
appropriate use of publicly sourced real estate information, and to be open and
honest in disclosing how that information is used.</P>
<P>3)Balance:   We only offer products and services that assure a favorable
balance of consumer benefits when weighed against privacy expectations.</P>
<P>4)Security:   We protect information from unauthorized access or alteration.</P>
<a name="xiii"></a>
<p><b><u>XIII. REIPA's Fair Information Practices (FIP):</b></u>
<P>1)Legal and ethical conduct: We commit to and practice the highest level of
legal and ethical conduct in dealing with customers, consumers and data
suppliers.</P>
<P>2)Reputable sources:  We acquire data from reputable sources -- within and
without the government -- and take reasonable precautions to ensure and maintain
the accuracy of that data.</P>
<P>3)Openness to consumers: Recognizing that consumers have an interest in the
information we maintain,  we will be open about the type of information stored,
where it was acquired, and how it is used.</P>
<P>4)Use of our data:   We will know how the information we provide our
customers is going to be used, and we will assure that it is not used to
disadvantage consumers.</P>
<a name="xiv"></a>
<P><b><u>XIV. Access to Publicly Sourced Real Estate Data Should be Unrestricted and
at the Cost of Reproduction</b></u>
<P>Accordingly, based on  society's need for information and our responsible
use, we affirm the traditional American practices and values of open records:
</P>
<P>1) Access to publicly sourced real estate data should be  unrestricted.
Information companies are challenged to add value to it and rigorously practice
responsible use.   </P>
<P>2)The cost should be that of efficient reproduction in paper and/or computer
time, staff and materials.  The government does not exist to subsidize the
private sector, neither should it make the public record into a &quot;profit
center&quot;, nor initiate new programs based on the speculative prospect of
selling government data, nor should it seek to radically limit the release of
data fields in the publicly sourced data; nor should it demand royalties from
dubious copyright claims, nor enter into exclusive licensing arrangements; all
of which practices have the effect of restricting access to the public record
and producing a less efficient and innovative real estate marketplace.</P>
<a name="xv"></a>
<b><u>XV. Government Information Dissemination Principles
</u></b>
<p>
        Governments at all levels should adopt information dissemination positions governed by a set of principles including:
<ol>
<li> The government does not exist to subsidize the private sector, nor should it
attempt to compete against it;
<li> the public record should not be turned into an agency's  "profit center",
<li> agencies should not initiate new programs based on the speculative prospect of selling government data;
<li> agencies should not limit the release of data fields in the publicly sourced
data, unless there is a compelling threat of individual harm or disadvantage;
<li> agencies should not demand royalties nor claim copyright on public record data;
<li> agencies should not enter into exclusive licensing arrangements;
All of these practices have the effect of restricting access to the public record and producing a less efficient and innovative real estate marketplace. Moreover because they harm the free market and damage commercial businesses they retard
 tax collections and the creation of jobs.
</ol><p>


<a name="xvi"></a>
<p><b><u>XVI. Ongoing Study</b></u>
<P>Moving forward, REIPA is committed to responsible use of public data. 
REIPA's members know that information can be abused.  Thus, REIPA is studying
the impact of free flowing information so that the highest professional and
ethical standards for the use of information are disseminated to its members.
</P></BODY></HTML>
</DOC>
