<HEAD>
<TITLE>PRESS RELEASE</TITLE></HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor=ffffff>
<font size=-1>
<br>REI Providers Association
<br>1420 16th St. NW, Washington, DC 20036
<br>Contact: Randy Dyer, CAE
<br>Phone: (202) 328-7460
<br>FAX: (202) 332-2301
<br>E-mail: <a href="mailto:reipa@aol.com">reipa@aol.com</a> </font>
<P><strong>FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE<p>
<em><center>ACCESS TO PUBLIC INFORMATION UNDER ATTACK</center></em><p></strong>
<em>REI Industry Forum to be held in San Francisco</em>
<P><em><strong>Washington, D.C., September 25 </strong></em>~ The emerging information age has found
government agencies seeking to limit access to public information, according to
Professor Earl Epstein of Ohio State University.  Open access to information is
an integral element in the nature and extent of citizen participation in the
economy and politics, Epstein claims.  It is a tradition that dates back to the
time of John Locke and Thomas Jefferson.  Efforts by state and local governments
to control the terms and conditions of access to public information is a serious
encroachment on this fundamental principle of our democracy.</P>
<P>Professor Epstein will be one of the featured speakers at the Annual
Business Meeting and 1996 Fall Conference of the REI Providers Association
(REIPA) scheduled to take place October 26 - 27, 1996 at the Westin St. Francis
Hotel in San Francisco, California.  He will join Roger Hurlbert of Sage
Information Services and Rufus Lusk, III of Experion Property Data on the
keynote session entitled &quot;Access to Public Information.&quot;</P>
<P>The two day program also features a session on the use of geographic and
spatial information titled, &quot;GIS is More than Maps.&quot;  Panelists
include Lynn Sites, DataQuick Information Systems;  Dan Cotter, Transamerica
Information Services;  and Steve Trammel, ESRI.  &quot;The Changing Face and
Pace of the Appraisal Industry&quot; will be addressed by Barry Bates, Vice
President and Chief Appraiser for The Money Store; and Mark Keegan, Senior Vice
President of  Lender's Services, Inc. Moderating the panel will be Howard Sears,
MAI, SRA, President, Market Data Research, Inc.  Other sessions include a
program on personal data as it relates to real property transactions entitled, &quot;Demographics:
 Putting the 'Who' into 'Where' &quot;; a session on information sourcing
through the World Wide Web entitled, &quot;Internet/Intranet Tools &amp;
Technology Trends&quot;; and a program aimed at real estate information
providers entitled &quot;Creating Proprietary Commercial Property Databases.&quot;
 As a special feature of the Conference, Cameron King, Executive Vice President,
Electronic Commerce, Countrywide Home Loans, will present an overview of the
role of real estate information in the mortgage industry.   </P>
<P>On Sunday, October 27, REIPA will present its Venture Fair, including a
Company and Product Showcase.  This marketplace of real estate information
products and services will feature companies with innovative and emerging
products as well as a chance for industry members to review partnership and
investment opportunities.  More than eighty investment, banking and venture
capital firms have been invited to attend.</P>
<P>Registration for the Conference is open to REIPA members and non-members
alike.  Those interested in attending should contact the REI Providers
Association at (202) 328-7460, by fax at (202) 332-2301, or via e-mail at
<a href="mailto:reipa@aol.com">reipa@aol.com</a>.  Registration can also be completed through the REIPA website at
<a href="http://www.reipa.com">http://www.reipa.com</a>. Additional information on the Association is available
from W.B. Freeman, President and Chairman of the Board of Directors, at
515-255-2088.</em></P></BODY></HTML>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>WT05-B02-114</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA081-000561-B022-62</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://www.reipa.com:80/Industry/Press/pr050396.html 207.120.161.17 19970103125241 text/html 3720
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Date: Fri, 03 Jan 1997 12:52:24 GMT
Server: Apache/1.0.5
