<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//IETF//DTD HTML//EN">

<html>

<head>
<title>newideas</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p><font color="#408080"><font size=5><strong>Auburn Drive: A New School With New 
Ideas</strong></font></font></p>
<hr>
<p align=center><img src="eagle1.jpg" align=bottom></p>
<hr>
<p>Auburn Drive High School is located in a new subdivision in Cole 
Harbour and draws its students from both the rural heritage of historic 
Halifax County and the modern suburban growth of Dartmouth. The 
mix in many ways parallels the hopes for the school, to combine the 
past and the future into a unique educational facility for the present.</p>
<p>Feeder schools for Auburn Drive are Graham Creighton, Astral Drive, 
and Gaetz Brook Junior Highs. Graham Creighton, the region's first high 
school before the construction of Cole Harbour District High, serves 
the suburban areas of Westphal as well as the tradition-rich 
Afro-Canadian communities of East Preston and Cherry Brook. 
Contrasting with historic Graham Creighton, the youthful exuberance of 
Astral Drive reflects its role as one of the youngest and fastest growing 
schools in Nova Scotia. Its students are mainly drawn from the Colby 
Village development and adjacent subdivisions and in a few short years 
the school has grown to challenge Graham Creighton's traditional lead 
in academic excellence, music and sports. Gaetz Brook, located amid 
the beauty of the Eastern Shore, will send some of its graduates to 
Auburn Drive. These will come mainly form the Lake Echo region, an 
area known internationally for its aquatic sports and the producer of 
several national and world champions.</p>
<p>The nature of these schools reflects the diversity of the human resources 
at Auburn Drive High. To fully meet the needs of its students at the 
close of the 20th century and into the 21st, the school will minimize the 
concept of education within the confines of walled classrooms. The 
needs of the students will be combined with those of teachers, 
community, and the world beyond, each contributing to the education of 
the other on a cross referenced network of learning. As a part of this 
commitment, educational partnerships have been formed with Pratt and 
Whitney, Maritime Tel and Tel, Royal Bank Of Canada, and technical 
courses will combine the community and the school in unique learning 
activities. The compulsory Exploring Technology course at the Grade 
Ten level will introduce students to many of the learning activities. The 
award-winning Applied Broadcast Journalism and Applied 
Broadcasting Technology courses link their services as well as other 
programs to the school, to the community, province, nation and 
beyond.</p>
<p>As a communications and educational hub, Auburn Drive High School 
will be reaching out and at the same time drawing in to create a new, 
flexible type of school and a new way of learning needed to face 
present and future educational challenges.</p>
<hr>
<p align=right><a href="index.htm">Back To The Main Menu</a></p>
</body>

