<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//IETF//DTD HTML//EN">

<html>

<head>
<title>Current Affairs - Survey - Wade MacDonald</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p align=center><b>Current Affairs - Survey</b></p>
<p>About 3 weeks ago I decided to run a survey within Auburn Drive High School's newly 
established e-mail system. Since all students have access to e-mail, I thought this was a good 
medium to post a survey, and I was quite impressed with the results. Here are the results to the 
survey, &quot;How the CBC cuts affect high school students?.</p>
<p>I will first start off with the facts, which some of you may or may not know. Late in the day on 
Thursday, September 19, 1996, the Canadian Broadcasting Corporation's President, Perrin 
Beatty, announced to CBC employees and various media the cuts which the CBC would face 
over the nest 18 months. The cuts which face the CBC all have to do with </p>
<p>the Government reducing spending on the Crown Corporation. Examples of the cuts include $127 
million cut from their annual budget, bringing the total cuts in budget up to $414 million since 
1995. Furthermore, 2500 jobs are to be lost, totalling about 4000 since 1995. Although there will 
be no closures of local stations, there will be program changes. Locally produced shows such as 
&quot;Up on the Roof&quot; (on the English TV network) and &quot;Mainstreet&quot; (on English Radio) are thought to 
be on the chopping block. CBC also wants to achieve it's original mandate by September, 1998, 
with an all Canadian television network, cutting all American shows at all times of the day.</p>
<p>I didn't know what reaction I would get from high school students on this subject, but I was 
pleased with the 19% reply rate. 29 out of 150 randomly chosen students replied, and this is what 
they had to say about the CBC.</p>
<p>To start off, I asked how had been aware of the cuts before they happened. 19 students said they 
knew about the cuts. </p>
<p>I wanted to know about the viewing and listening habits of the students, and I asked several 
questions on the subject. I found out that nearly 59% of respondents watched the English 
television network on a regular basis. 7% rarely watched. With radio, I wasn't really surprised to 
find that the vast majority of respondents rarely listened to the service, with the remainder tuning in 
now and then. However, with the CBC Stereo service, it pleased me to find 7% listened to it on a 
regular basis. About 83% rarely listened. </p>
<p>Since Canada is a bilingual country, and the CBC reflects this, I asked about the French services. 
7% tuned in to French television, in addition to 7% who both listened to French radio and 
watched French TV. </p>
<p>In conclusion to the survey, I asked the students if they felt CBC should aim more programming 
towards the younger generation. The vast majority, 79%, wanted programming based towards 
their own age, while the remainder, 21%, felt the CBC should not change its programming 
towards this generation. </p>
<p>Additional comments were welcome, and were received. Here are a few of those which I 
received.</p>
<p>CBC should focus more on our generation because we are the future. We </p>
<p>need to learn as much as we can now about future jobs etc. CBC should </p>
<p>focus more on teen issues and stop treating &quot;our&quot; problems as no big </p>
<p>deal. Teenagers are often portrayed as the problem in society there </p>
<p>should be less age discrimination in the media in general.</p>
<p>I think the CBC is far too regulated to be a successful media </p>
<p>force in today's society. The only way it will attract more interest </p>
<p>is if it breaks free of Canadian Government regulations and sponsors </p>
<p>people-oriented programming, instead of educational programming. I </p>
<p>rarely watch TV so it makes little difference to me, but that's the </p>
<p>way I see it. :)</p>
<p>I don' believe they should be cutting CBC at all. In my opinion CBC is </p>
<p>watched by more people I know then any other channel. </p>
<p>I think that there should be more programs for our </p>
<p>generation, but not solely our generation. It should have a balanced </p>
<p>variety so that it will appeal to more people and perhaps then the </p>
<p>cuts won't be necessary</p>
<p>I believe that the CBC offers a valuable service to the </p>
<p>Canadian people and culture. SRC offers good programming of a </p>
<p>professional nature in french. This is something hard to find on </p>
<p>other french networks. Both CBC and SRC provide the Canadian and </p>
<p>Maritime views on several issues. This not available on American </p>
<p>stations and is not shown enough on various other Canadian stations </p>
<p>such as CTV and MITV. </p>
<p>They want to make it more&quot;Canadian&quot;,and that is a good idea </p>
<p>THEORETICALLY, but people are not going to watch something unless they </p>
<p>want to. They probably won't watch it just because it is Canadian. </p>
<p>They should concentrate on Canadian shows, but don't rule out the </p>
<p>American shows altogether.</p>
<p>I would like to thank all those who participated in the survey; it was a great help! :) My next 
survey, which I will be sending out on Monday (***subject to approval***) will be on the Justice 
system... the perception of it and the Young Offenders Act, from a high school standpoint. </p>
<p>Also, the results of this survey are being sent to the CBC radio program &quot;As It Happens?, a 
current affairs program on CBC Radio (90.5 FM in Halifax), airing Monday to Friday from 6:30 
to 8:00 PM. </p>
<p><b>-Wade MacDonald</b></p>
<p><a href="paprmain.htm">Back</a></p>
</body>

</html>
</DOC>
