<HEAD>
   <TITLE>Trade Management</TITLE>
   <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Mozilla/3.01Gold (Win95; I) [Netscape]">
</HEAD>
<BODY color="#ffffff">

<P><!-- <BODY background="sandpapr.gif" color="#ffffff"> --></P>

<H1 ALIGN=CENTER>Trade Management</H1>

<P><IMG SRC="stripe.gif" ALT="----------------------------------" HEIGHT=4 WIDTH=540></P>

<P>Unlike any other mutual funds, Fidelity Selects are priced hourly starting
at 10 am EST and ending at 4 pm EST. Whenever you place a trade it will
be executed at the next pricing. If you place a trade after the markets
close or at any time before 10 am the next day, the trade will be executed
at the 10 am prices. If you want the trade to be executed at the closing
prices then you should call Fidelity between 3 pm and 4 pm. </P>

<P>Being able to trade on the hour allows a <B>trade management strategy</B>
which, if applied on a consistent basis, enhances the STS returns. </P>

<P>This strategy is suitable for investors who can follow the markets between
9:30 am and 10 am (or at the very least for investors who can make one
phone call to Fidelity during that half-hour to gauge the markets). If
your schedule does not permit this, then you should probably place the
trades the night before and they will be filled at the opening hour (10
am). </P>

<P>We have looked into the intraday behavior of the Selects for the last
five years. The most apparent pattern is that Selects tend to have their
extremes at either the opening (10 am) or the closing (4 pm) time. More
than any other hour, the highs and lows of the day occur either at the
opening or at the close. </P>

<P>Since the Selects are correlated to the general market, <I>statistically
speaking</I>, a Select fund will have its daily low at the opening and
its daily high at the close if the markets are strongly up that day. Conversely,
<I>statistically speaking</I>, a fund will open at its daily high and close
at its daily low if the markets are strongly down that day. </P>

<P>The markets open at 9:30 am and any trade placed before 10 am will be
filled at the 10 am price. Knowing the above statistical behavior of funds,
this extra &quot;free&quot; half-hour allows us to do some intelligent
&quot;trade management.&quot; </P>

<P>If you follow STS, there are three possible ways to trade: </P>

<UL>
<LI>from cash into a fund </LI>

<LI>from a fund into cash </LI>

<LI>from a fund into a fund </LI>
</UL>

<P>Here is how we try to trade each case. </P>

<UL>
<LI>Cash to fund </LI>

<UL>
<LI>If the markets are strongly up between 9:30 am and 10 am (Dow-Jones
up over 30 points, for example), then it is best to buy the fund at the
10 am pricing because it is likely to close at or near its daily high.
</LI>

<LI>If the markets are strongly down, it is better to wait and buy the
fund at the close because it is likely to close at or near its daily low.
</LI>

<LI>If the markets are hard to read, then it is probably best to buy the
fund at the 10 am pricing to get it over with. </LI>
</UL>

<LI>Fund to cash </LI>

<UL>
<LI>If the markets are strongly up between 9:30 am and 10 am then it is
best to wait and sell the fund at the 4 pm pricing because it is likely
to close at or near its daily high. </LI>

<LI>If the markets are strongly down, it is better sell the fund at the
10 am pricing because it is likely to close at or near its daily low. </LI>

<LI>If the markets are hard to read, then it is probably best to sell the
fund at the 10 am pricing to get it over with. </LI>
</UL>

<LI>Fund to fund. </LI>

<UL>
<LI>If the markets are strongly up between 9:30 am and 10 am then it does
not matter when you switch because it is likely that both funds will be
rising as the trading day goes on. So it is probably best to switch funds
at the 10 am pricing just to get it over with. (Or, based on some information
beside STS, <I>you</I> may decide to wait until the close.) </LI>

<LI>If the markets are strongly down, it is better (i) to sell the fund
you currently own at the 10 am pricing (because it is likely to be at or
near its daily high at that time), (ii) wait until the close, and then
(iii) buy the new fund at the close (because it is likely to close at or
near its daily low). </LI>

<LI>If the markets are hard to read, then it is probably best to switch
funds at the 10 am pricing just to get it over with. </LI>
</UL>
</UL>

<P>The more recent trades shown at our <A HREF="http://www.dollarlink.com/record.sht">real-time
trading record at the STS Web site</A> have either opening or closing prices.
That is because we have been applying this trade management strategy.
</P>

<P><I>Please note that the strategy is based on statistical data and does
not work every time.</I> Sometimes what looked like a strong bull market
at 9:50 am may turn into a strong bear market by 4 pm. Markets are notoriously
fickle, especially intraday. However, the strategy should pay off if applied
consistently over the long run. </P>

<P><A HREF="http://www.dollarlink.com">To STS home page</A> | <A HREF="about.htm">About
Timing Laboratory</A></P>

<P>[ <a href="http://www.webtools.org/counter/">115</a>]</P>

