            ---------------------------------------------------
                       Concepts Behind DollarWin
            ---------------------------------------------------


DollarWin is a quantitative, momentum-based stock/fund picking
computer system built on the premise that

       STOCKS/FUNDS THAT RISE IN PRICE MUCH FASTER THAN THE REST OF 
       THE MARKET CONTINUE TO OUTPERFORM THE MARKET FOR SOME TIME.

For purposes of this newsletter, the DollarWin system focuses exclusively
on mutual funds, although it has been successfully applied to stocks.

DollarWin measures price trends for hundreds of mutual funds and then ranks
these mutual funds relative to each other using the price trend as a
measure of relative strength or weakness.

We have researched and fine-tuned the parameters that comprise the core of
DollarWin for many years.  The algorithms in DollarWin use various
technical analysis tools (such as moving averages, oscillators, MACD, On
Balance Volume, Money Flow, Fibonacci Numbers), statistical tools (such as
standard deviations, volatility measures and bands, chaos theory), as well
as proprietary pattern recognition decision-making rules.

In effect, DollarWin performs technical analysis on hundreds of price
charts SIMULTANEOUSLY in order to identify mutual funds that meet or exceed
the criteria for price performance.

Initially, DollarWin ranks all mutual funds in a specific universe (for
example, Fidelity FundsNetwork or Schwab's OneSource) and "buys" the top,
say, 4 mutual funds.  Every day thereafter, DollarWin continues to rank all
the mutual funds in the universe.  If a mutual fund has fallen out of the
top 4 based on our proprietary sell criteria, it is replaced by another
that has come up and meets the buy criteria.  If there are no suitable
replacement candidates, DollarWin "sells" and keeps the proceeds in cash. 
The next week, the procedure is repeated to see if a new candidate has
appeared.  The aim is always to be as fully invested as possible.  However,
it is possible, especially in a declining market, that DollarLink will stay
in cash because there may be no funds that meet DollarLink's rather
stringent acceptance criteria.

Keep in mind that this is a momentum-type system and it needs to "see" a
trend before it can make a decision.  Thus, it will never buy in early or
sell out early.  It will always be a bit late.  However, the
high-performing funds have quite a bit of inertia and will continue in the
same general direction for some time.  

Of course, since the system depends on analyzing trends, it cannot react
to short-term unpredictable events -- such as a sudden crash.  We have a
"stop-loss" rule designed for a fund that is sinking rapidly: if a fund is
down more than N percent from the highest high while we owned it, sell.  N
is typically about 6% to 8%; it depends on the volatility of the fund.

We have performed extensive computer simulations with the DollarWin system
to substitute for a long-term "track record." It has been tested on various
stock and mutual funds universes with up to 10 years of historical data. 
The historical back-testing has been as realistic as possible.  It includes
the cost of commissions as well as the effect of bid and ask spreads.  For
mutual funds it includes the cost of switching funds due to loads and
switching penalties.

Based on historical computer simulations, DollarWin delivers good total
returns.  For the universe of mutual funds comprised of Fidelity
FundsNetwork plus Fidelity Selects, DollarWin achieved about 200% since
1/1/91.

Although not available through this newsletter, DollarWin also achieved
excellent simulated results in its stock portfolios.  For a conservative
stock universe (such as the S&P 100 stocks), it achieved 1,400% total
return over a period of 10 years.  For a riskier universe comprised of high
technology stocks, it gave about 600% over a period of 5 years.  These
returns were achieved assuming a 5-stock portfolio strategy.

If you are interested, call DollarLink Software at 415-641-0721 for more
information on DollarWin and our computerized back-testing.









            ---------------------------------------------------
                      How To Use This Report
            ---------------------------------------------------

We, the editors of this report, use the DollarWin system every day to trade
our own accounts of stocks and mutual funds.  We also provide daily trading
advice to a sister investment company that manages money directly for its
clients.

This Signal Report uses the DollarWin system every week to rank a carefully
selected universe of mutual funds.  It then makes buy, sell or hold
recommendations.

There are over 5,000 publicly traded mutual funds in the U.S.  Rather than
trying to rank all of them -- an enormous and not necessarily more
rewarding job -- DollarWin concentrates on a smaller group of time-proven
mutual funds families.  The universe of mutual funds we have chosen --
about 350 funds -- is comprised of all the no-transaction-cost funds in the
Fidelity FundsNetwork, all the Fidelity Select Portfolios funds and the
Rydex funds.

Fidelity FundsNetwork is an association of 10 mutual fund families.  All
transactions are conducted through Fidelity Brokerage Services at no cost
to the client.  Fidelity Brokerage acts as a custodian for all your fund
positions and it is a convenient mechanism to switch mutual funds between
Fidelity as well as the other funds families.  For further information,
call Fidelity at 800-544-9697.  By using the FundsNetwork you eliminate the
inconveniences of dealing with several fund families, all at no cost to
you.

Fidelity Select funds have a 3% up-front load.  However, there is no fee to
switch between Select funds once you have bought one.  We include the
Selects in our universe because they have demonstrated a superior
performance over the years IF they are monitored closely.

Please note that DollarLink Software is not associated in any way (except
as a customer) with Fidelity Investments, Fidelity Brokerage or the
FundsNetwork.  We get absolutely no remuneration from Fidelity.  We use
Fidelity because it is a convenient mechanism for switching funds.

The concept of funds network was popularized by Charles Schwab Brokerage
(800-266-5623) and Jack White Brokerage (800-323-3263).  We have
back-tested DollarWin on both Schwab's and White's universes, but decided
to use Fidelity's FundNetwork because we have found its funds to be more
profitable in the long run.  The big difference is Fidelity itself: neither
Schwab nor White have Fidelity funds in their universes, and Fidelity
funds, especially the Selects, are usually near the top of all funds.

[In the spring of 1994 Muriel Siebert and Waterhouse Securities have also
started their own mutual funds networks, but they are not as comprehensive
as Schwab, White or Fidelity.]

The Rydex Funds are not in the FundsNetwork but we include them because one
of them, Ursa (RYURX), can act as a hedge against a bear market.  Ursa is
designed to be the opposite of the S&P 500 index.  Another, Nova (RYNVX) is
designed to copy the S&P.  Rydex funds have to loads nor switch penalties. 
You can buy them directly from Rydex (800-820-0888) or, if you're willing
to pay a small commission, through Jack White or Fidelity.

We have set up four aggressive model mutual fund porfolios classified by
the number of funds in the portfolio and by the type of funds in the
portfolio.  The Two-Fund portfolio usually gives the highest returns but is
the most volatile.  (We have found the Two-Fund portfolio to have less risk
and about the same returns as a one-fund portfolio.) The Four-Fund
portfolio is usually more diversified and less risky but also gives lower
returns.  The 4-Fund Selects-only portfolio chooses funds only from the
Fidelity Select sector funds.  It is about as risky as the regular
four-fund portfolio.  The Eight-Fund portfolio is the least risky.

The more funds in a portfolio, the less risk but also the lower the
potential return.  Since we are guided by performance strength,
diversification is not a specific DollarWin goal, although it is certainly
an important consideration in the selection process.  Keep in mind that
since we are going after maximum returns, the funds that we select are very
likely to underperform the general market during a decline, but should also
outperform the market during a rise.

Our model portfolios assume $20,000 starting capital for the Two-Fund
portfolio, $40,000 for the Four-Fund portfolio and the 4-Fund Selects
portfolio, and $80,000 for the Eight-Fund portfolio.  You can follow the
DollarWin system with any amount of money; our assumed starting capital is
a convenient starting point.

Our asset allocation strategy is simple: starting capital is split in equal
shares for all funds.  Thus, in the Four-Fund portfolio, you would allocate
$10,000 for each fund.

Each week DollarWin may recommend a buy or sell signal.  If you don't
already own the funds recommended by DollarWin, after you receive the
DollarWin report, you should place the trade during the next trading
session before the close.  It will be executed at the close of that
session.

In the case of Fidelity Select funds, their trades can be executed sooner
than the close: every hour on the hour during trading.  However, through
experience, we have not found that to be advantageous and we trade at the
closing prices.

If you are just getting started, decide which model portfolio you are going
to follow and start synchronizing yourself to the model portfolio by buying
the recommended "buy" funds for that portfolio.  Do not buy the funds in
the portfolio that we classify as "hold" and wait until we either sell them
or reclassify as a "buy."

If you have been following the system and are currently holding a partially
filled portfolio, wait until there is a "buy" on a fund that is not in your
current portfolio.

The DollarWin reports do not account for the cost of loads and switching
(if any).  On the other hand, we also exclude the interest that the account
may earn while not fully invested, as well as all dividends.

Based on historical back-testing, our optimized buy/sell criteria generates
a switch for a position roughly every 38 calendar days, on average.  Such
frequent switching may trigger switching penalties.  For example, the
Fidelity Select funds charge 0.75% of assets if you hold a fund less than
30 days.  Some other Fidelity funds will charge 1.5% to switch if you hold
a fund less than 90 days.  For other fund families, the switching penalties
vary; some are more forgiving than others, but in general they are similar
to Fidelity.

In our extensive back-testing we assumed a conservative and uniform 2%
switching penalty EVERY TIME we sold a fund.  DollarWin still produced very
impressive returns.  Our research has convinced us that properly timed
switching is a much more important consideration than the cost of
switching.










            ---------------------------------------------------
                             Risk Factors
            ---------------------------------------------------

Investing in mutual funds is speculative and involves a high degree of
risk.  The DollarWin system has not been applied over a significant period
of time in real trading.  Recommendations made in the future may or may not
equal or better the performance of DollarWin as simulated by historical
back-testing.  Because the DollarWin system is intended to identify stocks
or mutual funds whose price is increasing, it may not perform as
anticipated in a flat or generally declining market.  Even in a generally
rising market, DollarWin may not outperform the market or may not result in
any profits at all to investors following its recommendations.  Past actual
or simulated performance is no guarantee of future results.



            ---------------------------------------------------
                             Disclaimer
            ---------------------------------------------------

This report is not a complete analysis of every material fact representing
any mentioned entity.  Opinions are subject to change without notice. 
Statements of fact have been obtained from sources believed to be reliable
but no representation is made to their accuracy or completeness. 
DollarLink Software or persons associated with it may at times be long or
short any stocks or mutual funds noted in this report and may at times buy
or sell such stocks or mutual funds.

            ---------------------------------------------------
                              End Of Report
