<TITLE>DollarLink News -- August 31, 1996</TITLE>

<!-- <BODY background="sandpapr.gif" color="#ffffff"> -->
<BODY color="#ffffff">

<A name="dlinktop"></a>

<center>
<IMG SRC="dlink.gif" ALT="[DollarLink Logo]"><p>
</center>

<h1>DollarLink News -- August 31, 1996</h1>

<IMG SRC="stripe.gif" ALT="----------------------------------"><p>
  

<h2> 
Enhancements Added
</h2>

<h3> 
1200 Maximum Symbols in Portfolio
</h3> 

By squeezing a few things here and there, we were able to extend the 
maximum number of symbols in a DollarLink portfolio from 1000 to 1200. 
It is set in Question 20, Part 1 of SETUP.
<p>

To use this option effectively, make sure that your PC has at least 
600K of the lower 640K of RAM free.  It is very important that the 
lower 640K (as opposed to the  extended  memory, which your 
PC may have in abundant amount) is as unoccupied as possible.  Your 
PC's memory manager program  --  EMM386.SYS or QEMM386.SYS, for example 
should be able to take care of that.
<p>

Also, if you are getting quotes on stock options and want to increase 
the number of symbols in the portfolio to 1200, make sure to tell 
DollarLink to load incoming option quotes into high memory (Question 
25, Part 1 of SETUP).  This will free up some of the lower 640K RAM.

Keep in mind that on the Signal datafeed the receivers can hold no 
more than 1200 symbols in the user portfolio. (The enhanced Signal 
receivers can also keep up to 64,000 quotes in a separate  instant 
quotes  database, but that's different from the  user  
database.)
<p>

