<TITLE>DollarLink News -- July 31, 1996</TITLE>

<!-- <BODY background="sandpapr.gif" color="#ffffff"> -->
<BODY color="#ffffff">

<A name="dlinktop"></a>

<center>
<IMG SRC="dlink.gif" ALT="[DollarLink Logo]"><p>
</center>

<h1>DollarLink News -- July 31, 1996</h1>

<IMG SRC="stripe.gif" ALT="----------------------------------"><p>
  

<h2>Enhancements Added</h2>

<h3>Bid/Ask Prices in Hot Quotes</h3>

Hot Quotes are the 10 little windows that appear at the bottom of 
the screen when you are in graphics mode. You can tell DollarLink 
to display any symbol in one of these hot quotes windows by pressing 
WH (Windows, Hot Quotes). Hot Quotes can be turned on or off by pressing 
the Home key while you are in graphics mode. Whenever the datafeed 
sends a quote for a symbol in a hot quote window, that information 
is updated in the hot quote.
<p>

If the information displayed is too long for the hot quote window, 
you can toggle between long and short display mode by pressing Alt+V 
keys. DollarLink will toggle between displaying the name and the hot 
quote window letter (followed by the price information).
<p>

Until now, the information displayed was the latest price and change 
from yesterday. <b>You can now display bid/ask price information instead 
of the last price/change information</b>. This should be useful for option 
traders as well as for short-term stock traders who use bid/ask information 
as part of their decision-making.
<p>

The Alt + V key combination will now rotate between 1) long names 
and price/change, 2) short names and price/change, 3) long names and 
bid/ask, and 4) short names and bid/ask. Just keep pressing the Alt 
+ V until the display shows what you need.
<p>

<h2>Vote For DollarLink!</h2>

<i>Technical Analysis of Stocks & Commodities</i> magazine has an 
annual Reader's Choice Awards survey. Readers of the magazine vote 
for the investment software and datafeeds they prefer. DollarLink 
has always scored highly in this survey, either winning or placing 
in its category.
<p>

This year, probably due to their sloppiness, DollarLink's name is 
missing on the voting ballot. The ballot went out to magazine subscribers 
early this month. What is odd is that DollarLink is listed in the 
<i>Portfolio Management</i> and <i>Options Analysis</i> categories, 
but not in its bread-and-butter <i>Real-Time Technical Analysis</i>
category.
<p>

If you subscribe to this magazine, please fill out the ballot and 
write in DollarLink in the <i>Professional Platform</i> category 
(that's where DollarLink was listed last year and where it won honorable 
mention), as well as in the  <i>Software &gt;  $500</i> category.
<p>

Please help us correct this (unintentional, we are told) oversight 
by  <i>Stocks & Commodities</i>. Thank you. 
<p>

<h2>Labor Day Holiday</h2>

DollarLink Software will be closed on Labor Day, Monday, September 
2, 1996.
<p>

