<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//IETF//DTD HTML 3.2//EN">
<HTML>
<HEAD>
   <TITLE>Paint Chip Repair</TITLE>
   <META NAME="Author" CONTENT="John Paterek">
   <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Mozilla/3.0b5aGold (Win95; I) [Netscape]">
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="pap42.jpg">

<H1 ALIGN=CENTER>Restoration Tips! </H1>

<H2 ALIGN=CENTER>PAINT CHIP REPAIR</H2>

<CENTER><P><B><FONT SIZE=+1>By John Paterek</FONT></B> <BR wp="br1">

<HR WIDTH="100%"></P></CENTER>

<P>Now that the <B><FONT COLOR="#008000">911</FONT></B> is the lone Porsche
on the assembly line, the <B><FONT COLOR="#FF0000">Porsche</FONT></B> factory
has decided to switch to base/clear on solid colors. <FONT COLOR="#FF0000"><B>Mercedes</B>
</FONT>has used this process with success for many years. <B><FONT COLOR="#FF0000">BASF</FONT></B>
has developed water borne base coat colors and solvent based clear. </P>

<P>The Germans were required to reduce VOC (volatile organic compounds)
levels and the amount of lead in formulas. <B><FONT COLOR="#FF0000">Porsche</FONT></B>
also discontinued the sale of touchup paint (which never really matched)
due to its flammable contents. The result is no source for color other
than <B><FONT COLOR="#008000">Glassurit</FONT></B> paint sold at auto supply
shops. You need only 1/2 oz. of color to touchup chips for years. </P>

<P>Chip maintenance should be done after each wash, especially after track
events. The surface should be cool to the touch and done in a non-windy
area. Airborne dust will stick to new paint. <B><I>Never</I></B> sand the
area prior to touchup. This will promote rub through or uneven surface
near the chip. I like to use a tiny artist brush. It allows control of
color to be applied. Remember to clean wax out of the chip with a toothpick.
The surface can also be cleaned with a <B><FONT COLOR="#408000">Q-tip</FONT></B>
and a small amount of non-oily nail polish. Apply touchup in two applications
to a level surface. </P>

<P>Minor polishing with a mixture of <B><FONT COLOR="#408000">Imperial
Hand Glaze and Blue Magic</FONT></B> can help level the surface. Wrap a
piece of T shirt around a metal bottle cap and use as a buffing block.
This is done after required drying time of 1 to 2 weeks has elapsed. Remember
the chip can penetrate four layers: clear, base coat, white primer, black
wash primer. Some rocks can upset the primer and leave rough edges around
the crater. Smooth this off with your fingernail. Remember not to be too
aggressive. A gnat size chip can grow to a fully repainted hood, and that
could be a $700.00 mistake. </P>

<P>
<HR WIDTH="100%"></P>

<CENTER><P><FONT SIZE=-1>Page Last Modified: </FONT>Monday, 09-Sep-96 12:20:40 EDT</P></CENTER>

<CENTER><P><FONT SIZE=-1>Local Date: Friday, 07-Feb-97 21:07:46 EST(Clear
Your Cache if Not Correct!)</FONT></P></CENTER>

<CENTER><P><A HREF="http://www.pit-stop.com/restore"><IMG 
SRC="homelogo.gif" BORDER=0 ></A><BR>
Back to the Restoration Tips home page. </P></CENTER>

<CENTER><P><FONT SIZE=-1>Site Designed and Developed by <A HREF="http://www.pit-stop.com">Pit-Stop
Internet, Ltd.</A> Copyright,1996. </FONT></P></CENTER>

</BODY>
</HTML>
