http://stover.web.galaxy.net:80/restore/paintmatch.shtml 207.111.84.73 19970208020751 text/html 3069
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Date: Sat, 08 Feb 1997 02:08:00 GMT
Server: Apache/1.1.1
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//IETF//DTD HTML 3.2//EN">
<HTML>
<HEAD>
   <TITLE>Non-Factory Tinted Paint</TITLE>
   <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Mozilla/3.0b5aGold (Win95; I) [Netscape]">
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="pap42.jpg">

<H1 ALIGN=CENTER>Restoration Tips! </H1>

<CENTER><P><B><FONT SIZE=+1>By John Paterek</FONT></B> </P></CENTER>

<CENTER><P>
<HR WIDTH="100%"></P></CENTER>

<CENTER><P><B><FONT SIZE=+2>Question</FONT></B> </P></CENTER>

<P>I own a '65 <B><FONT COLOR="#008000">356C</FONT></B> coupe. The previous
owner had the Ruby Red <B><FONT COLOR="#FFFF00"><FONT SIZE=+1>color tinted
darker than original</FONT></FONT></B>. I need to refinish the left quarter
panel, any <B><FONT COLOR="#FFFF00"><FONT SIZE=+1>suggestions for a match</FONT></FONT></B>?
Also the problem of &quot;fish eyes&quot; in the final coats of urethane.
Any product recommendation?&quot; </P>

<P>
<HR WIDTH="100%"></P>

<CENTER><P><B><FONT SIZE=+2>Response</FONT></B> </P></CENTER>

<P>Paint match problems are on the rise now that the EPA has removed lead
from most primary colors. Reds are in that category. They also turn darker
or more purple with age and ultraviolet exposure. <B><FONT COLOR="#FF0000">Du
Pont</FONT><FONT COLOR="#408000"> Paints</FONT></B> now has a <B><FONT COLOR="#408000">Chroma
vision camera</FONT>.</B> It is a hand held device that shoots three pictures
of your color and then feeds the data to Dupont's color library. A formula
in chroma base color is produced. The system is a base coat/ clear coat
process. It works! I have had 10 to 12 successful matches using this process.
It is great for original sun faded colors reducing the need for total overall
refinishing. The fisheye problem is a painters nightmare. They are small
crater like voids in the finished color coat. Fish eyes can be repaired
with a drop of color and careful sanding but only on solid colors. The
cause is poly silicones used in wax and polish formulas. To remove, use
a product called <FONT COLOR="#408000"><B>Polycracker prep wash solution</B>.</FONT>
(201-335-2828). It is sprayed on with a mist bottle prior to refinishing
of body panels, wheels and engine sheet metal. It removes all traces of
contaminants therefore giving a fisheye free finish with little effort!
They also make a great silicone free hand cleaner designed for the painting
industry to remove contaminants from your hands. <BR wp="br1">

<HR WIDTH="100%"></P>

<CENTER><P><FONT SIZE=-1>Page Last Modified: </FONT>Monday, 09-Sep-96 12:23:50 EDT</P></CENTER>

<CENTER><P><FONT SIZE=-1>Local Date: Friday, 07-Feb-97 21:08:00 EST(Clear
Your Cache if Not Correct!)</FONT></P></CENTER>

<CENTER><P><A HREF="http://www.pit-stop.com/restore"><IMG 
SRC="homelogo.gif" BORDER=0></A><BR>
Back to the Restoration Tips home page. </P></CENTER>

<CENTER><P><FONT SIZE=-1>Site Designed and Developed by <A HREF="http://www.pit-stop.com">Pit-Stop
Internet, Ltd.</A> Copyright,1996. </FONT></P></CENTER>

</BODY>
</HTML>
