<HTML>
<HEAD>
   <TITLE>Instrument Guages</TITLE>
   <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Mozilla/3.0b5aGold (Win95; I) [Netscape]">
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="pap42.jpg">

<H1 ALIGN=CENTER>Restoration Tips! </H1>

<CENTER><P><B><FONT SIZE=+1>By John Paterek</FONT></B> </P></CENTER>

<P>
<HR WIDTH="100%"></P>

<CENTER><P><B><FONT SIZE=+2>Question</FONT></B> </P></CENTER>

<P>&quot;The <FONT COLOR="#FFFF00"><B><FONT SIZE=+1>gauges</FONT></B> </FONT>on
my '71 <FONT COLOR="#008000">91IT</FONT> that I recently rescued from a
3 year stint in a musty garage have the typical <B><FONT COLOR="#FFFF00"><FONT SIZE=+1>damage
from sun fading and fogging</FONT></FONT></B>. How do I disassemble them
for cleaning? I am retaining the original faces but wonder if day glow
orange paint can be purchased for the tach and speedo needles, any help?&quot;
</P>

<P>
<HR WIDTH="100%"></P>

<CENTER><P><B><FONT SIZE=+2>Response</FONT></B> </P></CENTER>

<P>The gauges are exposed to the same film inside them as your <B><FONT COLOR="#008000">911</FONT></B>
windows are. Smoking, dampness and plasticsizers from the upholstery will
fog gauges. Some ship them to be rebuilt, but the bezel can be removed
with a dull blade knife. Carefully roll the edge of the bezel. They are
black anodized or painted metal and will open without bending out of shape.
Remove the glass, clean with detergent, anti fog could be used but just
clean works best. Paint the needles with day glow orange aerosol sprayed
into the cap and carefully brush on the needle. It should dry flat in tone.
Clean the faces with a mild detergent, dry and reassemble. Place the clean
glass in a new bezel (purchased from <B><FONT COLOR="#FF0000">North Hollywood
Speedometer</FONT></B>), check under glass for dust or fingerprints. Press
the face down on a clean table and reroll the bezel with a plastic screwdriver
handle. It will bend but it is time and patience. <B><FONT COLOR="#008000">356</FONT></B>
gauges are assembled the same way with new bezels (chrome plated brass).
Press the edge carefully to prevent cracking of the chrome. <B><FONT COLOR="#FF0000">North
Hollywood Speedometer</FONT></B> does a great job of assembly; just remind
them not to reset your odometer to ZERO! <BR wp="br1">
<BR wp="br2">
</P>

<P>
<HR WIDTH="100%"></P>

<CENTER><P><FONT SIZE=-1>Page Last Modified: </FONT>Monday, 09-Sep-96 12:29:44 EDT</P></CENTER>

<CENTER><P><FONT SIZE=-1>Local Date: Friday, 07-Feb-97 21:08:26 EST(Clear
Your Cache if Not Correct!)</FONT></P></CENTER>

<CENTER><P><A HREF="http://www.pit-stop.com/restore"><IMG 
SRC="homelogo.gif" BORDER=0 ></A><BR>
Back to the Restoration Tips home page. </P></CENTER>

