<HTML>
<HEAD>
   <TITLE>Metal Targa Trim</TITLE>
   <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Mozilla/3.0b5aGold (Win95; I) [Netscape]">
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="pap42.jpg">

<H1 ALIGN=CENTER>Restoration Tips! </H1>

<CENTER><P><B><FONT SIZE=+1>By John Paterek</FONT></B> </P></CENTER>

<P>
<HR WIDTH="100%"></P>

<CENTER><P><B><FONT SIZE=+2>Question</FONT></B> </P></CENTER>

<P>I have a 1980 <B><FONT COLOR="#008000">911 SC Targa</FONT></B>. I would
like to<B><FONT COLOR="#FF0000"> </FONT><FONT COLOR="#FFFF00"><FONT SIZE=+1>restore
the metal trim and the out side insignia</FONT></FONT></B> etc. There seems
to be two types of metal involved, the rear window lower trim and the type
around the triangular front window. The Targa roll bar is in decent condition
but will need to be repainted in the future. </P>

<P>My question is how to go about restoring these surfaces. What grit of
sand paper to use, whether to sand the front window trim which looks like
its anodized, was the <B><FONT COLOR="#008000">Targa</FONT></B> lettering
black originally. I would like to know the easiest way to mask the body
or any tricks you might have in this area. What is the best type of paint?&quot;
<BR wp="br1">

<HR WIDTH="100%"></P>

<CENTER><P><B><FONT SIZE=+2>Response</FONT></B> </P></CENTER>

<P>The roll bar on your 1980 <B><FONT COLOR="#008000">SC Targa</FONT></B>
is stainless steel painted matte black. Scripts on <B><FONT COLOR="#008000">SC</FONT></B>'s
are black anodized aluminum as well are trim moldings around the windshield
rear window, vent and door top trim. Door handles are black anodized pot
metal. </P>

<P>You can restore color to the <B><FONT COLOR="#008000">911SC</FONT></B>
script and <B><FONT COLOR="#008000">Targa</FONT></B> scripts. Remove rear
deck script, sand with 320 and spray with <B><FONT COLOR="#FF0000">Wurth</FONT><FONT COLOR="#408000">
Matte Black</FONT></B>. You can mask the <B><FONT COLOR="#008000">Targa</FONT></B>
script by placing paper behind the script carefully. Mask the bar and paint
with <B><FONT COLOR="#FF0000">Wurth</FONT></B>. I would suggest painting
the entire roll bar and script as a unit, after dry sanding the roll bar
with 320 wet or dry. Degrease the surface with <B><FONT COLOR="#FF0000">Ditzler</FONT></B>
wax and grease remover or <FONT COLOR="#FF0000"><B>Dupont</B> </FONT><B><FONT COLOR="#408000">3812S</FONT></B>.
Remove the rear upper glass seal from the bar and mask the entire body
with 6 mil plastic. Mask over the interior (top off) blow off the bar to
remove any dust in the script and apply 3 coats <B><FONT COLOR="#FF0000">Wurth</FONT><FONT COLOR="#408000">
Matte Black</FONT></B>. </P>

<P>You can gun spray with <B><FONT COLOR="#408000">Glasurit Rally Black</FONT></B>
but the <B><FONT COLOR="#FF0000">Wurth</FONT></B> gives the best finish.
Use a respirator and spray in a warm garage with little air flow. You can
also apply this process to door handles and moldings. Be certain to mask
the entire body. Over spray can find its way into the slightest opening.
Be certain to include the fresh air vent on the cowl. Matte Black can be
applied to <B><FONT COLOR="#008000">944</FONT></B> door handles and <B><FONT COLOR="#008000">911</FONT></B>
plastic deck grills that turn gray. 
<HR WIDTH="100%"></P>

<CENTER><P><FONT SIZE=-1>Page Last Modified: </FONT>Monday, 09-Sep-96 12:31:38 EDT</P></CENTER>

<CENTER><P><FONT SIZE=-1>Local Date: Friday, 07-Feb-97 21:08:41 EST(Clear
Your Cache if Not Correct!)</FONT></P></CENTER>

<CENTER><P><A HREF="http://www.pit-stop.com/restore"><IMG 
SRC="homelogo.gif" BORDER=0 ></A><BR>
