<HTML>
<HEAD>
   <TITLE></TITLE>
   <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Mozilla/3.0b5aGold (Win95; I) [Netscape]">
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="pap42.jpg">

<H1 ALIGN=CENTER>Restoration Tips! </H1>

<CENTER><P><B><FONT SIZE=+1>By John Paterek</FONT></B> </P></CENTER>

<CENTER><P>
<HR WIDTH="100%"></P></CENTER>

<CENTER><P><B><FONT SIZE=+2>Question</FONT></B> </P></CENTER>

<P>I own an '87 <B><FONT COLOR="#008000">911</FONT></B> with the original
<B><FONT COLOR="#FFFF00"><FONT SIZE=+1>Bosch headlights</FONT></FONT></B>.
Recently I had to replace a lamp due to rock damage. The <B><FONT COLOR="#FFFF00"><FONT SIZE=+1>new
one is crystal clear, the old quite foggy</FONT></FONT></B>. Is there a
way to clean this? </P>

<P>
<HR WIDTH="100%"></P>

<CENTER><P><B><FONT SIZE=+2>Response</FONT></B> </P></CENTER>

<P>The lamp does have access. Remove the bezel and four screws that hold
the assembly to the bucket. Remove the retainer and bulb. I used an acid
brush with a small amount of glass cleaner. Tape the brush to a pencil
for extra length. There are also surgical swabs that can remove additional
residue. The lens will remain clear if cleaned every year or two. <BR wp="br1">

<HR WIDTH="100%"><BR wp="br2">
<center><FONT SIZE=-1>Page Last Modified: </FONT>Monday, 09-Sep-96 12:33:04 EDT</P></center>

<CENTER><P><FONT SIZE=-1>Local Date: Friday, 07-Feb-97 21:08:51 EST(Clear
Your Cache if Not Correct!)</FONT></P></CENTER>

<CENTER><P><A HREF="http://www.pit-stop.com/restore"><IMG 
SRC="homelogo.gif" BORDER=0 ></A><BR>
Back to the Restoration Tips home page. </P></CENTER>

