<HTML>
<HEAD>
   <TITLE>Non-Acid Rain or Water Marks?</TITLE>
   <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Mozilla/3.0b5aGold (Win95; I) [Netscape]">
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="pap42.jpg">

<H1 ALIGN=CENTER>Restoration Tips! </H1>

<CENTER><P><B><FONT SIZE=+1>By John Paterek</FONT></B> </P></CENTER>

<CENTER><P>
<HR WIDTH="100%"></P></CENTER>

<CENTER><P><B><FONT SIZE=+2>Question</FONT></B> </P></CENTER>

<P>I am the proud owner of a new <b><FONT COLOR="#008000">993</FONT></b>. It has
metallic paint and came through without a mark on it. Recently, while <b><FONT COLOR="#FFFF00"></b>under
fluorescent light</FONT></b>, I noticed <b><FONT COLOR="#FFFF00">water spot rings
on the roof and sunroof panel.</FONT></b> Is this acid rain? How can I remove
it and what other steps would you recommend to keep my car perfect? <BR wp="br1">

<HR WIDTH="100%"></P>

<P><center><P><font size=+2><B>Response</B></font>
</P></center></P>

<P>The spots you mentioned are mineral deposits from rain. Acid rain is
a pock mark deep in the surface usually from years of neglect. I have removed
this deposit by using <b><FONT COLOR="#FF0000">3M</FONT> <FONT COLOR="#008000">Imperial
Hand Glaze</FONT></b> and a small clean section of cotton towel. Polish by
applying the glaze to the towel, buff in one general direction rubbing
until the ring disappears. If this approach fails, place a tiny amount
1/4&quot; of <b><FONT COLOR="#008000">Blue Magic</FONT></b> to the cloth already
covered with <b><FONT COLOR="#FF0000">3M</FONT></b>. Again care must be used not
to over buff at once. New <b><FONT COLOR="#FF0000">Porsches</FONT></b> need polishing
and waxing to prevent this condition. The metallic base coat is now water-based
with traditional baked enamel clear. It is already hard enough to wax when
delivered. Do so with a good quality canuba wax. Other areas of concern
on the <b><FONT COLOR="#008000">993 </FONT></b>would be the area directly behind
the front wheels. The stone guards are absent. I would make a pair from
<b><FONT COLOR="#008000">911 C2 Turbo</FONT></b> plastic stone guards. Perhaps
the factory will install them as they are aware of the problem. Enjoy your
<b><FONT COLOR="#008000">993</FONT></b>! </P>

<P><HR WIDTH="100%"><p>
<center><font SIZE="-1">Page Last Modified: Thursday, 05-Sep-96 23:06:01 EDT</font></center></p>
<p><center><font SIZE="-1">Local Date:  Friday, 07-Feb-97 21:09:02 EST (Clear Your Cache if Not Correct!)</font></center></p>
<center><A HREF="http://www.pit-stop.com/restore"><img src="homelogo.gif" BORDER=0></A></center><br>
<center><A> Back to the Restoration Tips home page.</A><BR wp="br1">
<BR wp="br2">
<CENTER><P><FONT SIZE=-1>Site Designed and Developed by <A HREF="http://www.pit-stop.com" border=0 >Pit-Stop
Internet, Ltd.</A> Copyright,1996. </FONT></P></CENTER>
