<HTML>
<HEAD>
   <TITLE>Mufflers</TITLE>
   <META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Mozilla/3.0b5aGold (Win95; I) [Netscape]">
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="pap42.jpg">

<H1 ALIGN=CENTER>Restoration Tips! </H1>

<CENTER><P><B><FONT SIZE=+1>By John Paterek</FONT></B> </P></CENTER>

<CENTER><P>
<HR WIDTH="100%"></P></CENTER>

<CENTER><P><B><FONT SIZE=+2>Question</FONT></B> </P></CENTER>

<P>The <B><FONT COLOR="#FFFF00">muffler</FONT></B> on my'72 <B><FONT COLOR="#008000">91I
T </FONT></B>has developed some leaks and is due for replacement. I purchased
a used one that has no holes in it and is generally in good shape. What
technique would you suggest to <B><FONT COLOR="#FFFF00">clean this new/used
muffler to prepare it for painting</FONT></B>? And then, which paint will
last well? I'd like to paint it the original gray color for a stock appearance.
<BR wp="br1">

<HR WIDTH="100%"></P>
<P><center><P><font size=+2><B>Response</B></font></P></center></P>
<P>The muffler must be in good solid condition to stand up to sandblasting
for rust removal. You should cover the inlet and exhaust tips with duct
tape. The proper finish is available. It is called <B><FONT COLOR="#008000">VHT
1200 degree custom grey - 1041</FONT></B> from <B><FONT COLOR="#FF0000"><A HREF="http://www.stoddard.com">Stoddard
Imported Cars</A></FONT></B> in Ohio 1-800-342-1414. They sell it in quart
containers to be gun sprayed. 2 coats works well. Start the car after installation
and run only until the paint shows signs of smoking. Shut down the engine
and let cool. The next start up, the muffler will be cured and will not
burn off. <BR wp="br1">

<HR WIDTH="100%"></P>

<CENTER><P><FONT SIZE=-1>Page Last Modified: </FONT>Monday, 09-Sep-96 12:36:51 EDT</P></CENTER>

<CENTER><P><FONT SIZE=-1>Local Date: Friday, 07-Feb-97 21:09:12 EST(Clear
Your Cache if Not Correct!)</FONT></P></CENTER>

