<body background="sciroc1.jpg" bgcolor="#BC4C00" text="#000000" link="#C20008" vlink="#7E005C"alink="#B40000">

<h2><center><img src="trcspl2.jpg"</h2></center>
<hr width=100% align=center size=4>
<h3><left> Yes, you have entered the TRC Enterprises self promotion page.  I'm Tom Conklin,  I've started a small computer company out of my home northwest NJ that caters to small offices(SO) and home offices(HO). My specialty is building high quality, in

expensive, custom tailored computer systems. I also do repairs, upgrades, and consulting. My main focus is on DOS based systems, utilizing MSDOS, Windows, Windows95, and Windows NT. E-Mail me if you think I can help your small or home office.</left>

<hr width=25% align=center size=2>
<left>Although I don't do much in the way of programming I have done some stuff with Quick Basic. The biggest project I have done was programming a two axis overhead robot. It was originally designed to automatically clean machined parts in a hazardous ch

emical that has since been outlawed in several parts of the world do to the ozone. Now the robot is used more as a convenience item since the company now uses a much safer chemical. Other programming involved simple animated greeting cards. Again programm

ed in Quick Basic. I have the source code as well as the plans to build your own robot and with a little imagination  you can modify it to do almost anything. The source code for the greeting cards are good for students just learning to program. If anyone

 is interested in any of these  programs E-Mail me. My address is at the bottom of the page. </left>

<hr width=25% align=center size=2>
<left>I became involved with computers about ten years ago with an XT type computer. It had a 20mb mfm type HD and a whole 640 kb of memory, since then it has morphed into a Pentium 75 with a 1.6gb HD and 16mb of ram, Zoom 28.8 fax/voice/modem running Win

dows 95 and Windows NT 4.0 B2. Quite a jump from the old days. Combining all that was my love for sports cars and since I haven't been able to buy a Porsche yet, I grew up driving Volkswagons. I have owned six of them including my current '87 Scirocco 16v

 (background). Each one has served me well. That's how I got involved with Pit-Stop Internet. I happened to love sports cars (European type) and computers. Although I never tried my hand at web publishing before, I think I picked it up rather quickly. I n

ow do the <a href="http://www.pit-stop.com/clubs/clubs.html">Clubs</a> pages and the <a href="http://www.pit-stop.com/carpick">Car of the Month</a> page so have a look and tell me what you think.</left>

<hr width=25% align=center size=2>
<left>What's coming from TRC Enterprises? Well, I'm glad you asked. I am working on drawing my own graphics using Cadkey 7.0. It's a good cad program with a lot of capabilities. Check out the background on the main <a href="http://www.pit-stop.com/clubs/c

lubs.html">Clubs</a> page or the background on the <a 
href="http://www.pit-stop.com/clubs/scca1.html">SCCA</a> page, both were originally done in Cadkey. I have done more, but they are not auto orientated so they don't quite fit in with this site. I'm also

 trying to learn VRML. <a href="http://www.cadkey.com">Cadkey</a>  has a pretty neat program in the beta phase that you can download free. It looks and feels like Cadkey 7.0 so, if you are familiar with Cadkey 7.0 you'll be right at home. You can even loa

d your .prt files into it. Also any other projects Pit-Stop may throw at me,  keep checking there often as it is always evolving. That's enough to keep me busy for awhile. Don't forget to E-Mail me if  I can do something for your buisness or hobbies.</lef

t>

<hr width=100% align=center size=4>
 <a href="http://www.pit-stop.com/pitcrew/carsown.html">Cars owned</a>

<br><center><h4>Send any comments or suggestions to:
<a href="mailto:trcent@postoffice.ptd.net">TRC Enterprises</a></h4></center>

