<P><HR><FONT SIZE = "+2"><CENTER>May 1997</FONT></CENTER><HR><P>
<I>May 27
-30, 1997</I><BR>
<B>Soil Ecology: Understanding and Preserving Soil Systems</B><BR>
The 1997 Soil Ecology Society Conference will be held on the campus of Kansas State University in Manhattan, Kansas, from May 27-30, 1997. The meeting will begin Tuesday evening, May 27, with a keynote lecture and welcoming reception, and will end Friday, May 30.  The theme of the Conference (Soil Ecology: Understanding and Preserving Soil Systems) is designed to embrace current perspectives in soil ecology and highlight new advances in understanding the structure and function of belowground systems, with emphasis on the effects of natural and anthropogenic disturbances, and the role of soil ecology in ecosystem management. The program will include contributed oral presentations organized around session topics, afternoon contributed poster sessions, and opportunities for informal group discussions. Tentative session topics include: effects of natural and anthropogenic disturbances on soil biota and/or soil processes; soil food web dynamics; plant-microbial interactions; biogeochemical studies; rhizosphere ecology; and invertebrate-microbial interactions.  Special events will include a field trip and evening barbeque at the Konza Prairie Research Natural Area, a 3,500 ha tallgrass prairie preserve which is the focus for the grasslands ecology program at KSU. Additional local field trips will be arranged.  Registration materials will be mailed to all current SES members in November 1996.  Additional information and meeting updates can be found at <br>
<a
href="http://www-personal.ksu.edu/~jblair/ses.html">http://www-personal.ksu.edu/~jblair/ses.html</a>
<BR>
<I>From: Deborah Neher, University of Toledo</I>
<P>

