<HTML><HEAD>
<TITLE>People: Gail Feenstra</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR = #ffffff><IMG ALIGN=left SRC="/Images/sarephdr.gif" ALT="Header Icon"><BR CLEAR=all><HR>
<font size="+3"><center>Gail Feenstra</font><br>
<font size="+2">Food Systems Analyst<p>
Sustainable Agriculture Research and Education Program<br>
(916) 752-8408<br>
FAX: (916) 754-8550<br>
<A HREF="mailto:gwfeenstra@ucdavis.edu">gwfeenstra@ucdavis.edu</A><br>
</font></center>
<p><hr><p><blockquote>
Gail Feenstra is a senior writer and food systems analyst at the UC Sustainable Agriculture Research and Education Program.  Her interests lie in the area of working with university and community members to develop community food systems in California.  She is on the board of the California Sustainable Agriculture Working Group (SAWG) and also participates as a co-chair of the Community Food Security Committee of the California SAWG.  She has been involved in helping to organize a number of activities and projects that link farmers and consumers in California.  Gail is also a nutritionist with a background in nutrition education.  One of her goals has been to encourage nutritionists, anti-hunger advocates and sustainable agriculture groups in California to become coalition partners in building more sustainable food systems.<P>
</blockquote>
<B>Current/Past Projects:</b><blockquote>Gail has been working for the past several years, with Dave Campbell, SAREP's economic and public policy analyst on a project that links sustainable agriculture and community development.This project arose out of a growing recognition of the opportunities to connect the use of sustainable production practices with the economic and social development of California communities.  Initial funding came from a $2 million grant from the W.K. Kelloggs Integrated Farming Systems Initiative, which funded a three-year project directed by the California Alliance for Sustainable Agriculture (CASA), a new coalition of six non-profit groups and three university programs.  The community development work represents an important piece of the CASA project and has influenced a much broader network of researchers and practitioners in the sustainable agriculture movement.<P>
The goal of the project is to identify both general principles and concrete strategies which link sustainable agricultural practices to community development.  The following methods have been used to achieve this goal:<BR>
 a review of existing literature linking sustainable agriculture to community development,<BR>
 a review of new directions in "community-controlled economic development,"<BR>
 a review of existing local food systems across the U.S.,<BR>
 a survey of community food systems collaborations currently underway in California<BR>
 intentional networking with people in community food security, community economic development and sustainable agriculture areas,<BR>
 creation and support of the Sustainable Agriculture Working Group.<P>
Progress to date<BR>
Initial working papers about community economic development strategies and local food systems were drafted and reviewed by individuals within and outside DANR.  These papers were revised and subsequently presented at a conference on "The Politics of Sustainable Agriculture," held in Eugene, Oregon, in October 1995.  Since then, Local Food Systems and Sustainable Communities, by Gail Feenstra has been accepted for publication by the American Journal of Alternative Agriculture.  Community-controlled Economic Development as a Strategic Vision for the Sustainable Agriculture Movement by Dave Campbell is currently under consideration for publication by the AJAA.<P>
A community food systems bibliography with nearly 100 entries has been prepared, along with a two-page pamphlet "Steps for Developing a Sustainable Community Food System."  These materials along with the two papers have been widely distributed among interested parties in the state, including CE personnel, community organizations and university researchers.<P>
Currently, a survey is underway to identify and profile the most prominent community food systems in California.  We define a community food system as a collaborative effort to integrate local agricultural production with food distribution in order to enhance the economic, environmental and social well-being of a particular place (i.e., a neighborhood, city, county or region).  Although there is a growing interest in developing these community food systems nationwide, few have been documented.  Responses from the survey will be used to compile a publication which will document current activities, enable existing organizations to make connections and benefit from each others experiences, and analyze what can be done to encourage new and more effective collaborations.<P>
This October 2-3, SAREP is planning a major community food systems conference called, "Community Food Systems: Sustaining Farms and People in the Emerging Economy" which will bring together interested parties from across the state, showcase innovative work, and promote further reflection on the issues facing communities who wish to revitalize their food and agricultural economies.  The conference is co-sponsored by the Community Alliance with Family Farmers, the Community Food Security Coalition, the California Communities Program and SAREP.<P>
SAREP and the California Communities Program are currently in discussion with a nationwide research team to propose a USDA-funded study of "Local Food and Agricultural Systems in a Globalizing Environment." Along with grassroots organizing, more research of this kind is needed to assess the tangible social and economic benefits associated with developing community food systems. <P>
In addition to these projects, Gail is on the advisory board of the California Federation of Farmers' Markets.  She has been involved in discussions with the California Federation of Farmers' Markets and the USDA to develop a statewide consumer education campaign to promote farmers' markets.<P>
She is also on the board of the Agriculture, Food and Human Values Society.  She is participating with other board members in a project to improve communication and research initiatives among people across the country interested in community or local food systems.<P>
</blockquote>
<HR> [ <A HREF = "/">Home</A> | <A HREF="/cgi-win/sarep/sarepweb.exe">Calendar</A> | <A HREF = "/sarep/docs/search_sarep.html">Search</A> | <A HREF="mailto:sarep@ucdavis.edu">Feedback</A> ]<P>
</DOC>
