<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>RFP: 1996-1997 GRANTS FOR EDUCATIONAL EVENTS</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR = #ffffff>

<P>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="/Images/sarephdr.gif" ALT="SAREP Header Icon"><BR CLEAR=all>

<HR>

<H2><CENTER>REQUEST FOR PROPOSALS<BR>
</CENTER></H2>

<H2><CENTER>UNIVERSITY OF CALIFORNIA<BR>
SUSTAINABLE AGRICULTURE RESEARCH <BR>
AND EDUCATION PROGRAM<BR>
</CENTER></H2>

<H2><CENTER>1996-1997 GRANTS FOR EDUCATIONAL EVENTS<BR>
</CENTER></H2>

<H3>PROPOSALS DUE: AUGUST 1, 1996 </H3>

The UC Sustainable Agriculture Research and Education Program
(SAREP) is soliciting new proposals for grants to conduct educational
programs related to sustainable agriculture in California. Funds
are available to support workshops, field days, symposia, seminars,
and other educational events held between November 1, 1996 and
October 31, 1997. Awards are limited to $1,000 per event.
<P>
Those eligible to apply include individuals affiliated with California
public or private educational institutions, with California non-profit,
tax-exempt organizations, or with federal or state government
agencies. SAREP staff and members of SAREP's Public Advisory and
Technical Advisory Committees may not apply or participate as
cooperators on any proposals. Current Advisory Committee members
are: PAC- Catherine Brandel, Jenny Broome, Cynthia Cory, David
Costa, Leonard Diggs, Gail Gant, Marion Kalb, James Liebman, Ron
Mansfield, Andrew Rubin, Bryte Stewart, Michael Straus, Brock
Taylor, Don Villarejo and Angus Wright; TAC-Edith Allen, Tim Hartz,
Scott Johnson, Don Klingborg, Craig Kolodge, Juan Palerm, Terry
Prichard, Janet Savage, Tom Shultz, Rob Thayer, and Lucia Varela.
<P>
<HR>

<H3><CENTER>TOPICS and APPROACHES</CENTER></H3>

<P>
Meetings must relate to the three goals of sustainable agriculture:
environmental health, economic profitability, and social and economic
equity. Proposals will be accepted on a broad range of topics
and issues, but we are particularly interested in educational
events that address: 
<P>
The sustainability of crop and livestock systems. Topics in this
area include, but are not limited to: 
<UL>
<LI>Soil and water quality
<LI>Preventive approaches to pest management
<LI>Socio-economic impacts of alternative production practices

</UL>

<P>
The relationship between sustainable agriculture and the political,
economic, and social dynamics of the broader food system. Topics
in this area include, but are not limited to:
<UL>
<LI>Labor policies and practices
<LI>Land use
<LI>Rural community development
<LI>Public policy development
<LI>Marketing
<LI>Linking consumers, farmers and others in a sustainable food
system. 
</UL>

<P>
Please consult our publications for a fuller discussion of these
goals, and examples of past projects. Free publications include
a five-page paper, What is Sustainable Agriculture, the 60-page
Progress Report: 1993-1995, and the quarterly newsletter Sustainable
Agriculture. Order from UC SAREP, University of California, Davis,
CA 95616, telephone (916) 752-7556.
<P>
<I>Applicants are encouraged to consider the following details
when developing proposals.<BR>
</I><B>Instructors: </B>Speakers and presenters should be qualified
to teach the subject matter; expertise should also be drawn from
a range of backgrounds (farmers/ranchers, farm advisors, specialists,
other researchers, private consultants, etc.). 
<P>
<B>Hands-on activities:</B> Many successful educational programs
combine &quot;classroom&quot; activities with tours, demonstrations,
on-farm experiences and other activities that help participants
put ideas and concepts into action. 
<P>
<B>Educational methods:</B> A meeting format that emphasizes periods
of discussion, debate, problem solving or other types of audience
interaction is desirable. 
<P>
<B>Educational materials:</B> Participants will benefit from publications,
manuals, or handouts that participants can use when they return
to their farms and businesses. 
<P>
<B>Sponsorship: </B>The level of participation and the quality
of educational programs can be improved through cooperation among
complementary organizations (e.g., Cooperative Extension, private
non-profits, Natural Resources Conservation Service, and/or industry).
<P>
<HR>

<H3><CENTER>CRITERIA </CENTER></H3>

<P>
Proposals will be evaluated in three areas: 
<OL>
<LI>Relevance to the goals of sustainable agriculture and the
priorities of UC SAREP.
<LI>Identification of educational needs and objectives.
<LI>Likelihood that the proposed event will achieve the stated
objectives. 
</OL>

<HR>

<H3><CENTER>PROPOSAL FORMAT </CENTER></H3>

<P>
Applicants should complete the attached cover sheet (back cover),
including signatures, and provide a brief (2- or 3-page) proposal
with the following headings: 
<UL>
<LI>Goal of the Event (must include educational objectives, target
audience and estimated attendance) 
<LI>Importance of the Event (must include how it advances the
goals of sustainable agriculture) 
<LI>Proposed Agenda (must include topics, possible speakers, and
overall meeting format)
<LI>Approximate Date and Location (this RFP is for events held
between November 1, 1996 and October 31, 1997)
<LI>Sponsorship and Coordination (must include a description of
the roles of all coordinators and affiliates)
<LI>Handout Materials 
</UL>

<P>
<B>Budget<BR>
</B>A detailed budget should be listed on the cover page; write
down the total requested from SAREP in the space provided. Our
policy concerning budget items is listed below. Please read this
statement carefully. <B>Awards are limited to $1,000 per event.</B>
<P>
<B>Signatures<BR>
</B>Signatures of all coordinators and affiliates listed on the
cover page are required. These may be included in the space provided
on the cover page, or attached as a separate page. Signatures
will indicate that all project participants have read the proposal
and understand their roles in the proposed educational program.
<P>
<HR>

<H3><CENTER>HOW TO APPLY </CENTER></H3>

<P>
A signed original plus thirty copies (double-sided preferred)
of the application, using the prescribed format and cover page,
must be received by 5:00 p.m., August 1, 1996. Proposals that
are received after the deadline will not be reviewed. Proposals
will not be accepted via FAX. Proposals should be sent to: 
<P>
Meeting Grants<BR>
UC Sustainable Agriculture Research and Education Program<BR>
University of California<BR>
Davis, CA 95616
<P>
Physical location for delivery services: DANR Building, Hopkins
Road (off Hutchison Road west of Highway 113).
<P>
Proposals will be evaluated by the Public and Technical Advisory
Committees. Awards will be announced by November 1, 1996. If you
have any questions, call <A HREF="/sarep/staff/staff6.html">David Chaney</A> at (916) 754-8551 (e-mail:
dechaney@ucdavis.edu).<P>

<HR>

<H3><CENTER>POLICY CONCERNING BUDGET ITEMS FOR GRANTS FOR EDUCATIONAL
EVENTS</CENTER></H3>

<P>
Expenses covered by SAREP funds include: staff/personnel time,
travel and accommodations for speakers, travel for organizers,
room rental, speaker honoraria, equipment rental, and production
of handout materials. The budget can include a reasonable registration
fee, but the fee must be the same for all attendees: <I>You may
not offer registration discounts for members of particular organizations</I>.
The registration fee may be waived for individuals or groups who
might otherwise be unable to afford the cost of attendance (e.g.,
students, farm workers, low- income individuals). <BR>

<P>
<B>Budget items not covered by SAREP include the following:</B>
<OL>
<LI>Food and drinks. The cost of meals must be covered by the
sponsoring organization or included in the registration fee. 
<LI>Equipment purchase. SAREP funds may be used to rent equipment
necessary to conduct the meeting; funds may not be used to purchase
equipment. 
<LI>Instructor training. SAREP funds may not be used to pay registration
fees or travel for organizers or instructors to attend other meetings
or training events.
<LI>Video and audio taping. We generally do not provide funds
for this service unless a strong case is made for the use of the
recordings for other educational purposes. <BR>
</OL>

<P>

<HR>

<H3><CENTER>University of California
Sustainable Agriculture Research and Education Program
1996-1997 Grants for Educational Events </CENTER></H3>


<CENTER>Cover Page
Attach a completed copy of this page to each copy of your proposal.
</CENTER>
<PRE>


<B>Meeting Title




Principal Coordinator(s)</B>

Name                          Mailing Address           Telephone         email








<B>Affiliates</B>
Name                          Mailing Address           Telephone         email








<B>Detailed Budget</B>






Total Requested from SAREP _____________




<B>Signatures (all coordinators and affiliates)</B>







</PRE>

<HR>

<P>
