<HEAD>
<TITLE>RFP: 1996-1997 SUSTAINABLE AGRICULTURE GRADUATE AWARDS (SAGA)</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR = #ffffff>

<P>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="/Images/sarephdr.gif" ALT="SAREP Header Icon"><BR CLEAR=all>
<HR>

<H2><CENTER>REQUEST FOR PROPOSALS<BR>
UNIVERSITY OF CALIFORNIA <BR>
</CENTER></H2>

<H2><CENTER>SUSTAINABLE AGRICULTURE RESEARCH <BR>
AND EDUCATION PROGRAM <BR>
</CENTER></H2>

<H2><CENTER>1996-1997 SUSTAINABLE AGRICULTURE GRADUATE AWARDS
(SAGA)<BR>
</CENTER></H2>

<H3>Proposals Due: August 1, 1996 </H3>

<P>
We announce a competitive awards program for graduate students
conducting research in the field of sustainable agriculture. We
call this grant program Sustainable Agriculture Graduate Awards,
or SAGA. Registered graduate students (Master's or Ph.D.) attending
any accredited institution of higher learning in California are
eligible for SAGA. Students whose faculty advisor is a member
of SAREP's Public Advisory and Technical Advisory Committees are
not eligible.
<P>
Current members are: PAC- Catherine Brandel, Jenny Broome, Cynthia
Cory, David Costa, Leonard Diggs, Gail Gant, Marion Kalb, James
Liebman, Ron Mansfield, Andrew Rubin, Bryte Stewart, Michael Straus,
Brock Taylor, Don Villarejo and Angus Wright; TAC-Edith Allen,
Tim Hartz, Scott Johnson, Don Klingborg, Craig Kolodge, Juan Palerm,
Terry Prichard, Janet Savage, Tom Shultz, Rob Thayer, and Lucia
Varela. <BR>

<HR>

<H3><CENTER>CRIITERIA </CENTER></H3>

<P>
The criteria by which proposals will be judged are: 
<OL>
<LI>Contribution to achieving the goals of UC SAREP. 
<LI>Feasibility of obtaining the project goals by the methods
stated. 
<LI>Qualifications of the applicant.<BR>

</OL>

<HR>

<H3><CENTER>PRIORTIES </CENTER></H3>

<P>
All proposals should reflect a concern for the environmental,
economic, and social sustainability of California agriculture.
Briefly, our emphases include crop and livestock production and
community development and public policy. We strongly recommend
that applicants read our position paper What Is Sustainable Agriculture?
(available by calling SAREP at (916) 752-7556) and the UC SAREP
Request For Proposals for 1996-97 Research and Education Grants,
for background on our perspectives.<BR>

<P>
In crop and livestock production, our priorities include but are
not limited to: <B>soil management, habitat enhancement for biological
pest management, economic analysis, and concentrated animal production.
<BR>
</B>
<P>
In the arena of community development and public policy, we encourage
proposals concerning: <B>community food systems; marketing, consumer
education, and community food security; community economic development;
public policy; land use and the urban-rural interface; and labor
policies and practices. <BR>
</B>
<HR>

<H3><CENTER>FUNDING </CENTER></H3>

<P>
Each candidate may receive only one such award during her or his
graduate student career. The upper limit for individual awards
is $2,000, with the precise amount depending on the rankings of
the proposals received and the material requirements of the projects.
<BR>

<P>
<B>Use of Funds</B> <BR>
Funds may be used for the following purposes: 
<OL>
<LI>Supplies
<LI>Equipment (including computer software; any equipment obtained
becomes the Property of the university funded) 
<LI>Photocopying 
<LI>Special texts not readily available 
<LI>Farm equipment rental or operating charges 
<LI>Travel necessary for the project. 
</OL>

<P>
Funds may not be used for the following purposes: 
<OL>
<LI>Travel to scholarly meetings 
<LI>Computer hardware or time 
<LI>Preparation of thesis copy 
<LI>Stipend, salary, or scholarship 
<LI>Publication costs 
<LI>Purchase of classroom books 
<LI>Employment of assistants. 
</OL>

<HR>

<H3><CENTER>HOW TO APPLY </CENTER></H3>

<P>
A signed original plus thirty copies (double-sided preferred)
of the proposal must be received<B> by 5:00 p.m., August 1, 1996</B>.
Proposals that are received after the deadline will not be reviewed.
Proposals should be typed, single-spaced, 10 pt. font or larger.
No faxes will be accepted. Proposals should be sent to: 
<P>
UC Sustainable Agriculture Research and Education Program
<P>
University of California
<P>
Davis, CA 95616
<P>
Physical location for delivery services: DANR Building, Hopkins
Road (off Hutchison Road west of Highway 113).<BR>

<P>
The proposal must include the following sections: 
<P>
I. Title of proposed project. 
<P>
II. Names, addresses, institutional affiliations, and telephone
numbers of graduate student and major professor. 
<P>
III. Cooperating personnel and their roles in the project. 
<P>
IV. A summary of the proposed project (abstract), not to exceed
250 words. 
<P>
V. Body of the proposal, not to exceed 3 pages, including: 
<OL>
<LI>Significance of the proposed work in advancing the career
of the applicant, including the stage of the academic career that
this research will help to complete (i.e., Master's or Ph.D. degree,
academic department or program). 
<LI>How the proposed research advances knowledge in sustainable
agriculture. 
<LI>Rationale for the proposed study presented in the context
of related studies. 
<LI>Materials and methods for the proposed study, including timeline
for entire project. <BR>

</OL>

<P>
VI. Literature cited. 
<P>
VII. A resum&eacute; summarizing the candidate's accomplishments
and qualifications.
<P>
VIII. Detailed budget, including all sources of support. Justify
all items and indicate destinations and costs of trips. Use this
format:<BR>

<PRE>
<B>

            Item                     Amount
      (Specify Details)             Requested                Matching Funds 
                                  From UC SAREP          Amount         Source</B>

   Equipment

   Supplies and Expenses

   Travel



   <B>TOTALS</B>


</PRE>

<B>A letter of recommendation from the faculty advisor is required</B>.
This letter should arrive independently to <BR>
UC SAREP, and should include information on how the award would
help the student and advance the goals of<BR>
UC SAREP. This letter should also assess whether the student is
ready to undertake the proposed project and <BR>
whether the design of the project is adequate.<BR>

<P>
Proposals will be reviewed by the Public and Technical Advisory
Comittees. Awards will be announced by <BR>
November 1, 1996.<BR>

<HR>

<H3><CENTER>PUBLICATIONS AND FINAL REPORT </CENTER></H3>

<P>
UC SAREP requires one copy each of all theses, dissertations,
and other publications that are developed through <BR>
the funded studies, and a final report no later November 1, 1998.
<BR>

<P>
For further information, contact the UC SAREP office at (916)
752-7556 or sarep@ucdavis.edu<BR>

<HR>

<P>
<FONT SIZE=2>In accordance with applicable Federal laws and University
policy, the University of California does not discriminate in
any of its policies, procedures or practices on the basis of race,
religion, color, national origin, sex, marital status, sexual
orientation, age, veteran status, medical condition or handicap.
Inquiries regarding this policy may be addressed to the Affirmative
Action Director, University of California, Agriculture and Natural
Resources, 300 Lakeside Drive, 6th Floor, Oakland, CA 94612-3560.
(510) 987-0097. <BR>
</FONT>
<HR>

