<HEAD>

<TITLE>RFP: 1996-97 RESEARCH AND EDUCATION GRANTS FOR: CROP PRODUCTION LIVESTOCK PRODUCTION ENVIRONMENT, NATURAL RESOURCES, MARKETING, CONSUMER EDUCATION, AND COMMUNITY FOOD SYSTEMS </TITLE>

</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR = #ffffff>

<P>
<IMG ALIGN=left SRC="/Images/sarephdr.gif" ALT="SAREP Header Icon"><BR CLEAR=all>

<HR>

<H2><CENTER>REQUEST FOR PROPOSALS<P>
UNIVERSITY OF CALIFORNIA<BR>
SUSTAINABLE AGRICULTURE RESEARCH <BR> AND EDUCATION PROGRAM<BR>
</CENTER></H2>

<H3>PROPOSALS DUE: AUGUST 1, 1996<BR>
</H3>

<P>
<B>1996-97 RESEARCH AND EDUCATION GRANTS FOR:</B> 
<UL>
<LI>CROP PRODUCTION 
<LI>LIVESTOCK PRODUCTION 
<LI>ENVIRONMENT AND NATURAL RESOURCES
<LI>MARKETING, CONSUMER EDUCATION, AND COMMUNITY FOOD SYSTEMS

<LI>LABOR, LAND USE AND OTHER ECONOMIC AND PUBLIC POLICY ISSUES

</UL>

<P>
The University of California Sustainable Agriculture Research
and Education Program is soliciting proposals for new and continuing
research and education projects that will enhance the future of
California agriculture and the natural and human resources upon
which it depends. Sustainable agriculture integrates three goals:
environmental health, economic profitability, and social and economic
equity. Please consult our publications for specific methods and
examples that address these goals. Free publications include a
five-page paper, What is Sustainable Agriculture, our recent Progress
Report: 1993-1995, and the quarterly newsletter Sustainable Agriculture.
Order them from SAREP, University of California, Davis, CA 95616,
telephone (916) 752-7556.
<P>
SAREP actively seeks proposals from private non-profit groups
as well as UC investigators and researchers from other universities.
Projects that creatively link university faculty, UC Cooperative
Extension, farmers, and non-profit, community-based organizations
are particularly welcome. All investigators must be affiliated
with a California non-profit, tax-exempt organization.
<P>
We encourage proposals that exhibit a blend between a research
component which gathers reliable data, an educational component
which brings practical and timely information to targeted audiences,
and a demonstration or community development component which creates
new relationships, alliances, or institutions. Projects that are
not collaborative in nature or that focus exclusively on only
one of these three components will also be considered, especially
where it can be demonstrated that the results will be useful to
ongoing or future development of sustainable food and agricultural
systems. 
<P>
Projects may address either a single problem or a set of interrelated
problems that are critical to the sustainable functioning of a
particular farming, ranching, or food system. Proposals must clearly
demonstrate how the component in question is critical to the system
being studied, and how the results of the work can be integrated
into the whole agricultural system.<BR>

<HR>

<H3><CENTER>CRITERIA </CENTER></H3>

<P>
<B>All proposals will be judged according to the following criteria:</B>
<BR>
<B>Relevance: </B>Help achieve the stated goals and priorities
of SAREP, and be consistent with a holistic approach that simultaneously
weighs concerns for environmental quality, economic viability,
and social responsibility. 
<P>
<B>Team Approach:</B> Include on the project team people affected
by the project (especially farmers or farmworkers) and demonstrate
the ability of the proposal to foster collaboration which educates
and links a variety of players in the food system, including researchers,
farmers and farmworkers, farm advisors, non-profit groups, policymakers,
community organizations, and consumers. 
<P>
<B>Technical Merit:</B> Demonstrate the feasibility of fulfilling
objectives, the effectiveness of the methods proposed, and the
qualifications and relevant experience of the individuals and
organizations submitting the proposal. 
<P>
<B>Impact:</B> Produce new information, or make accessible existing
information, that reaches a significant audience and has a timely
and tangible impact. Tangible products are strongly encouraged.

<P>
<B>Cost-Effectiveness</B>: Provide evidence that the money requested
will be used effectively and is realistic given the objectives
of the project.
<HR>

<H3><CENTER>FUNDING PRIORITIES </CENTER></H3>

<P>
Projects that involve both crop and livestock production issues
as well as community development and public policy issues, and
that integrate the three goals of sustainable agriculture (environmental
health, economic profitability, and social and economic equity)
are particularly welcome. We wish to fund a mix of projects reflecting
the agricultural, geographic and ethnic diversity in the state-projects
useful to both large and small farmers and ranchers, as well as
consumers, farm workers, and other members of the public. The
specific possibilities mentioned in each area below are intended
to give suggestions but not to limit possible proposals. 
<H3>Crop and Livestock Production </H3>

<P>
Proposals are accepted on a variety of topics in production agriculture.
Generally, proposals should be explicitly linked to the principles
of sustainable farming practices that apply to innovations in
&quot;conventional&quot; agriculture as well as low-input and
organic agriculture. These principles include, but are not limited
to: 
<OL>
<LI>reduced reliance on off-farm inputs, especially fertilizers
and pesticides 
<LI>diversification of crops and/or livestock, surrounding habitat,
and other practices to enhance the biological and economic stability
of the farm or ranch
<LI>management of the soil to enhance and protect soil quality
and to prevent the off-site movement of soil nutrients
<LI>use of cultural practices that are least toxic and use the
least amount of nonrenewable energy. 
</OL>

<P>
Within these general principles, the following topics are of particular
interest:
<P>
<I><B>Soil Management</B></I> <BR>
Topics of research or education projects in this area may include,
but are not limited to:
<UL>
<LI>Improvement of soil fertility
<LI>Nutrient recycling
<LI>Improvement of soil structure and water penetration
<LI>Suppression of soil-borne pathogens
<LI>Erosion control 
</UL>

<P>
Suggested approaches include farming practices such as crop rotation,
cover cropping, addition of composts, manures, mulches, or similar
materials, micro and mesofauna enhancement, tillage practices,
and/or irrigation management, and proposals that lead to an increased
understanding of basic soil processes.
<P>
<I><B>Habitat Enhancement for Biological Pest Management</B></I>
<BR>
Projects are encouraged that increase our understanding of the
control of insect, weed, disease, or vertebrate pests through
the manipulation of habitats on or adjacent to cropland. Specific
practices may include:
<UL>
<LI>Crop rotation
<LI>Cover cropping
<LI>Use of insectary plants or hedgerows
<LI>Enhancement of riparian areas
<LI>Application of mulches
<LI>Installation of raptor nest boxes or perches
<LI>Other innovative biocontrol methods 
</UL>

<P>
<I><B>Economic Analysis</B></I> <BR>
Projects in this category include those that assess the costs
and returns to farmers and ranchers of different management practices
and systems. We are particularly interested in projects that compare
practices and systems that are thought to be more environmentally
and/or socially advantageous than those that are currently practiced.
The analysis should assess costs and returns within the current
economic and regulatory context, and also take into account potential
changes in that context over the short and long term.
<P>
<I><B>Concentrated Animal Production<BR>
</B></I>Concentrated livestock and poultry systems are very important
in California. They provide ways to use resources that people
cannot utilize, while providing high-quality products. Concentrated
production systems have issues of concern with respect to the
short- and long-term sustainability of California agriculture.
These issues include but are not limited to: 
<UL>
<LI>Waste management
<LI>Pathogen resistance to antibiotics
<LI>Natural resource use
<LI>Nutrient cycling
<LI>Input use
<LI>Animal welfare
<LI>Regulations
<LI>Labor use
<LI>Rural community effects 
</UL>

<P>
Proposals that address these issues or other factors related to
sustainable animal agriculture are invited.<BR>

<H3>Community Development and Public Policy </H3>

<P>
<I><B>Community Food Systems <BR>
</B></I>We are seeking to fund long-term, collaborative demonstrations
in particular places (i.e. a city, county, region, bioregion,
etc.) that take a holistic approach to developing a sustainable
community food system. SAREP funding could support new collaborations
or augment existing ones. The projects should work toward several
of the following goals and should be consistent with all of them:

<OL>
<LI>access by all community members to an adequate, affordable
diet of high nutritional value;
<LI>a stable base of family farms using production practices that
are less chemical and energy- intensive; 
<LI>marketing practices that create more direct and beneficial
links between farmers and consumers and to the extent possible
reduce the resources used to move food between production and
consumption; 
<LI>development of ag-related businesses that create jobs, recirculate
financial capital in the community, or in other ways contribute
to the community's economic development;
<LI>improved working and living conditions of farm labor such
that farmers and farmworkers can be fully contributing members
of the community; and 
<LI>public policies to encourage a community's transition to a
sustainable food and agricultural system by protecting farmland,
developing necessary infrastructure, and providing research and
technical assistance. 
</OL>

<P>
To be considered for a larger budget and/or a long-term commitment
of funding, proposals in this category should show clear evidence
of broad community support and involvement with the project, including
matching grants or in-kind contributions. Proposals should also
speak to the track record of project organizers in community-based
projects, identify tangible end products (reports, publications,
videos, etc.) that will result, and include a research or evaluation
component which produces tangible data on the project's economic
and social impacts on the community. 
<P>
<I><B>Marketing, Consumer Education and Community Food Security</B></I>
<BR>
We are seeking projects that facilitate direct marketing and/or
increase value-added returns to farmers; that develop or implement
strategies to educate consumers about their role in sustainable
food systems; or that improve access to fresh, affordable and
nutritious foods, particularly among low-income families in rural
and inner-city areas.
<P>
<I><B>Community Economic Development</B></I> <BR>
We are seeking projects that develop indicators, gather data,
and provide concrete analysis of how agricultural practices and
structures contribute to the viability or decline of California
communities; case studies of how the adoption of environmentally
sensitive agricultural production and marketing practices has
contributed or might contribute to community economic, social
and political development; or studies of how corporate concentration
and the emerging global economy impact the sustainability of California
agriculture.
<P>
<I><B>Public Policy<BR>
</B></I>We are seeking projects that develop concrete analyses
of the impact of federal, state and/or local government policies
and programs on the sustainability of agriculture in California;
develop criteria to assess current policies, and/or anticipate
the benefits, costs and political feasibility of policy alternatives;
create economic incentives that encourage growers, processors,
retailer and others to make the transition to sustainable agriculture;
or initiate Food Policy Councils as permanent institutional vehicles
for planning community food systems.
<P>
<I><B>Land Use and the Urban-Rural Interface</B></I> <BR>
We are seeking projects that address the threat to the sustainability
of California agriculture posed by rapid urban expansion on prime
soils and the potential for sustainable farming practices to help
ease this threat; that concretely document the existing and potential
impact of sustainable farming practices on agricultural conversion
patterns; or that promote mutual understanding and political cooperation
among urban residents and farmers.
<P>
<I><B>Labor Policies and Practices</B></I> <BR>
We are seeking research or community-based projects that improve
labor policies and practices to enhance sustainability, provide
critical data relating the conditions of agricultural labor to
the goals of sustainability; or use existing data to make comparisons
of how different farming practices impact labor; or otherwise
promote the full inclusion of agricultural laborers in decision-making
about the future of California agriculture.<BR>

<HR>

<H3><CENTER>ELIGIBILITY AND FUNDING </CENTER></H3>

<P>
Eligible applicants include researchers affiliated with California
public and private institutions of higher education or with California
non-profit, tax-exempt organizations. SAREP staff and members
of SAREP's Public Advisory and Technical Advisory Committees are
not eligible to participate as principal investigator, investigator,
or cooperator on any project. Proposals will be rejected if they
involve investigators or cooperators who are on SAREP's Public
or Technical Advisory Committees. Current members are: PAC- Catherine
Brandel, Jenny Broome, Cynthia Cory, David Costa, Leonard Diggs,
Gail Gant, Marion Kalb, James Liebman, Ron Mansfield, Andrew Rubin,
Bryte Stewart, Michael Straus, Brock Taylor, Don Villarejo and
Angus Wright; TAC-Edith Allen, Tim Hartz, Scott Johnson, Don Klingborg,
Craig Kolodge, Juan Palerm, Terry Prichard, Janet Savage, Tom
Shultz, Rob Thayer, and Lucia Varela. 
<P>
We are interested in funding a variety of small projects, with
typical awards of $3,000-15,000, but larger budgets will be considered
if well justified. Larger awards are reserved for integrative
and interdisciplinary projects that involve teams of researchers,
or for projects that link a range of players and constituent groups
within agriculture and the food system. Continued funding of larger
grants will be dependent on provision of matching funds or in-kind
contributions. Total funding for all grants (new and continuing)
is expected to be around $170,000. A number of projects funded
in 1995-96 are expected to apply for continuation funding, and
we expect the competition to be strong for both new and continuing
proposals.
<P>
Multiple-year projects should indicate total length (number of
years) at the time of the original proposal, with a work plan
and budget for up to three years. 
<P>
<B>Note: </B>Requests for Proposals for Graduate Student Awards
and for Educational Events (meetings, demonstrations, and field
days) are being made in separate documents, with different formats
for the requested proposals. The due date for these proposals
is the same (August 1, 1996) and both RFPs can be obtained by
contacting the SAREP office. <BR>

<HR>

<H3><CENTER>SUBMITTAL AND REVIEW SCHEDULE </CENTER></H3>

<P>
A signed original plus 33 copies (double-sided preferred) of the
<B>proposal must be received by 5:00 p.m., August 1, 1996</B>.
Proposals that are received after the deadline will not be reviewed.
Proposals will not be accepted via FAX. Proposals should be sent
to: 
<BLOCKQUOTE>
UC Sustainable Agriculture Research and Education Program<BR>
University of California<BR>
Davis, CA 95616
</BLOCKQUOTE>

<P>
Physical location for delivery services: DANR Building, Hopkins
Road (off Hutchison Road west of Highway 113).
<P>
All proposals will be reviewed by members of SAREP's Public and
Technical Advisory Committees. These include individuals from
farming and ranching, government, public organizations, and institutions
of higher education, all of whom are knowledgeable regarding the
issues and practices of sustainable agriculture. Where necessary,
additional peer review for scientific merit will be sought. Successful
applicants will be notified of awards by November 1, 1996. Applicants
from outside of the University of California should be aware that
additional time is required for transfer <BR>
of funds.<BR>

<HR>

<H3><CENTER>FORMAT </CENTER></H3>

<P>
Proposals must not exceed five single-spaced typewritten pages
(i.e. sections B-G), plus cover page, budget, literature cited,
and signatures and resumes of investigators (no more than one-page
resume per investigator). 
<P>
<B>A. Cover Page<BR>
</B>Use the cover page provided, or an exact duplicate of it,
for the requested information.
<P>
<B>B. Objectives</B> <BR>
A clear, concise, and complete statement of each specific research
or educational objective. Use measurable terms such as &quot;to
determine, to develop, to demonstrate&quot; rather than terms
such as &quot;to study, to investigate, to explore.&quot;
<P>
<B>C. Justification</B> <BR>
Describe the importance of the proposed research, and its linkage
to other sustainable agriculture concepts and results, including
environmental, social and economic impacts. Indicate the project's
potential for measurable progress toward long-term solution(s)
of the sustainability problem(s) you are addressing. Describe
how the project results contribute to the sustainable functioning
of the entire production system.
<P>
<B>D. Procedures</B> <BR>
For each objective discuss the research or educational methods
you propose to employ so they are understandable to both growers
and technical people. Indicate data to be gathered and analyses
to be used.
<P>
<B>E. Education and Outreach</B> <BR>
Describe the educational uses of the project. State when information
resulting from this project will be ready for implementation,
and what avenues of implementation will be used.
<P>
<B>F. Evaluation<BR>
</B>Describe how you will evaluate the degree of success of the
project. Formative evaluation, involving end-users in the planning
and development of the project, is strongly encouraged. In addition,
at appropriate times during and after the completion of the project,
the impact of your efforts should be evaluated. Consider ways
to evaluate longer-term and indirect effects of your project,
as well as shorter-term, direct impacts.
<P>
<B>G. Time Table</B> <BR>
Outline your timetable for initiating various phases of research
and education, and estimate the completion date(s). Identify delivery
date(s) of all milestones and products, including field days and
other outreach activities.
<P>
<B>H. Literature Cited</B>
<P>
<B>I. Budget</B> <BR>
Prepare a budget table for each fiscal year (ending June 30) up
to three years, in the following format. Show amounts and sources
of matching funds from the host institution or other sources.
If the proposed project is part of a larger project which is seeking
funds from other sources, describe briefly the related project(s)
and proposed funding source(s). No specific amount of matching
funds is required, but projects which show substantial matching
funds are desirable. For University of California investigators,
overhead is not allowed and funds allocated must be used by June
30, 1997 (or carried forward by request). For non-University investigators,
&quot;overhead&quot; must be clearly justified as direct costs
of the project.
<P>
<PRE><B>
                                        Requested                        Matching Funds
                                          Funds                        Amount      Source</B>

   Personnel:
     Name and/or payroll title 
      and % time
     Employee Benefits
   Employee Benefits 
   Supplies and Expenses (1)
   Permanent Equipment (2)
   Travel (3)

   TOTALS 

   __________ 

   (1) List by major category, with costs, and justification
   for categories over $500. Reimbursement of growers for potential
   crop loss is not allowed.

   (2) List specific items, their cost, and justification for
   each item. Equipment requests are scrutinized carefully, and are
   generally not approved unless the equipment is crucial to the
   project and access is not available by means other than purchase.

   (3) Indicate destination(s), estimate number of trips and
   cost of each.

</PRE>

   <P>
   <B>J. Participants, Approval and Signatures<BR>
   </B>Attach a one-page resume (no more than one page!) for each
   investigator. Provide a brief summary of each investigator's role
   in the project, including percentage of time committed to the
   project, signed by that investigator. Additional letters from
   cooperators are optional. The proposal should be approved and
   cosigned by the principal investigator and an official representative
   of the investigator's organization. 
   <P>
   <B>K. Mailing Label for Notification<BR>
   </B>If you wish to be notified that we have received your proposal,
   include a self-addressed mailing label with your proposal.
   <P>
   Cover Page-UC SAREP 1996-97 Research &amp; Education Proposals
   <BR>

<HR>

