<HTML><HEAD>
<TITLE>RFP: Extending Biologically Integrated Farming Systems
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR = #ffffff><IMG ALIGN=left SRC="/Images/sarephdr.gif" ALT="SAREP Header Icon"><BR CLEAR=all><HR>

<CENTER><H1>A Request For Proposals</H1><P><H2>Extending Biologically Integrated Farming Systems (BIFS)</H2><H2>For Field Crops, Row Crops, Orchards, Vineyards</H2>U.C. Sustainable Agriculture Research and Education Program (UC SAREP)<BR>University of California<BR>Davis, CA 95616<BR>916-752-7556<P><H3><I>Proposals Due: July 6, 1995</I></H3><P></CENTER>An increasing number of California farmers representing many commodities and counties have been able to maintain yields and quality while greatly reducing their reliance on agrichemicals, including pesticides and synthetic fertilizers. These farmers integrate the following elements into their production systems: <P><DL><OL><LI>Biological and cultural control of pests;<P><LI>	On-farm habitats for beneficial insects, mites, and spiders;<P><LI>	A strong emphasis on soil-building practices, often including biological nitrogen fixation to supply all or part of the nitrogen needed by crop plants;<P><LI>Reduced reliance on agricultural chemicals.</OL></DL><P> We call such production systems Biologically Integrated Farming Systems (BIFS). Many BIFS also employ additional tools, such as field monitoring for pest and beneficial organisms, collection of weather data, reliance on research-based action thresholds for decision making, use of selective biorational pesticides, and soil, water, and plant-tissue testing. BIFS are not necessarily limited to organic farming systems. Under BIFS management, agrichemical programs are crafted so as to interfere minimally with the integration of the elements mentioned above.<P> New legislation (Assembly Bill 3383) has enabled the University of California to award grants, for developing pilot demonstration projects for the purpose of extending BIFS methods. As described in the legislation, the projects will enable farmers to emulate regionally successful BIFS methodology. In essence, each funded project would be expected to transfer BIFS technology to 10-30 interested farmers, through technical support and farmer-to-farmer information sharing. The state legislature recognizes that a team outreach approach may help farmers learn and adapt integrated farming practices to local conditions most efficiently. To accomplish this, a management team of persons experienced in BIFS would provide technical support to a class of participating farmers. Such management teams should involve farmers, scientists, extension workers, and pest control advisers. Each applicant must outline a program which requires a maximum of 3 years of funding. Funds will be disbursed quarterly from invoices submitted. Renewed funding of ongoing projects contingent on demonstrated progress and available monies. Projects should be designed to be self-sufficient beyond the 3-year period. <P><B>Conflict of Interest Policy</B><BR>Members of Assembly Bill 3383 Program Advisory Review Board and UC SAREPs Public Advisory and Technical Advisory committees, and UC SAREP staff are not eligible to participate as Principal Investigator, Other Investigator, or Cooperator on any proposal for funding under this program. Proposals that involve the persons mentioned above will not be considered. <P><B>Eligibility</B><BR>Only individuals and institutions based in California may receive funding. The following people or groups are eligible to apply as principal investigator for a BIFS grant: private individuals, both for-profit and non-profit corporations, including commodity boards, Resource Conservation Districts, Natural Resources Conservation Service District or Soil Conservationists, University of California Cooperative Extension Farm Advisors, Cooperative Extension Specialists, Area IPM Advisors, and faculty of any accredited institution of higher learning in California. <P><B>Funding</B><BR>The funding for these awards is provided jointly by the California Department of Pesticide Regulation and the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency. Awards will range from $80,000 to $130,000 per year. <P><B>Use of Funds</B><BR>Principal expenditures should be for personnel, including the program coordinator, members of the management team, and persons who assist in field data collection and analysis. Funds may not be used for equipment purchases, unless these are clearly shown to be more economical than rentals. <P><B>Criteria</B><BR>The enabling legislation states that to the degree feasible, fundedprojects should be patterned after the Biologically Integrated OrchardSystems (BIOS) Project for almonds in Merced County (See <AHREF="#Appendix">Appendix</A>). Extension models other than BIOS may bemore appropriate in other crops, and we encourage applications which propose additional models for making BIFS accessible to farmers. <P> <DL><OL>The following principal criteria will be used to evaluate proposals:<P><LI> 	Has at least one Biologically Integrated Farming System, currentlyin use on a California farm, been identified that will serve as the template for the proposed outreach project?<P><P><LI> 	Have the practices employed on that BIFS farm been clearly documented? <P><P><LI> 	Does the proposed program address soil fertility, plant nutrition, and pest management decisions in the context of a whole system or at least multiple elements?<P><P><LI> 	Have the elements of the proposed BIFS technology been shown, through scientific studies, to reduce pest damage or incidence or to promote soil fertility?<P><P><LI> 	Does the proposed BIFS technology enable farmers to reduce reliance on synthetic fertilizer and biologically disruptive, non-selective pesticides? <P><P><LI> 	Does the proposal include a two- to three-year plan for extending BIFS to interested farmers and agricultural consultants?<P><P><LI> 	Has support been documented for the proposed BIFS outreach program from growers, appropriate commodity groups, and extension personnel? <P><P><LI>	Does the targeted conventional farming system employ relatively high total or per acre amounts of restricted-use pesticides, biologically disruptive, non-selective pesticides, or highly soluble nitrogen fertilizer? <P><P><LI>	Are current pest management strategies in the targeted conventional farming system threatened due to pest resistance, loss of pesticide registration, ineffective control, high costs or documented risk to health or the environment?<P></DL><P><B>Procedure and Timeline for Application, Evaluation, and Awards </B><BR>Twenty (20) copies of each proposal, typed, single-spaced, with 10 pt. font or larger, are due at U.C. Sustainable Agriculture Research and Education Program (UC SAREP), University of California, (DANR Building, Hopkins Road) Davis, CA 95616 by July 6, 1995, at 5:00 P.M. Faxed proposals will not be accepted. Proposals will be evaluated and ranked by the 13-member BIFS Program Advisory Review Board, and awards will be announced by August 4, 1995 and awarded promptly.The proposal must include the following sections:<P><B>I.</B> Title page, including:<DL><B>A.</B> Title of proposed project.<BR><B>B.</B> Name, address, institutional or corporate affiliation of theapplicant. Include telephone and FAX numbers, and, where applicable,e-mail address.<BR><B>C.</B> Names, addresses, and phone numbers of cooperatingindividuals and organizations and a statement of their roles in theproject. <P></DL><B>II.</B> 	A summary (abstract) of the proposed project, not to exceed250 words. <P><B>III.</B> Body of the proposal, not to exceed 10 pages, single-spaced,including: <P><DL><B>A.</B> A description of the Biologically Integrated FarmingSystem(s) and farm(s) which will serve as the basis for the extensioneffort. The following characteristics of the farming systems must bedescribed and where possible compared to county averages or conventions:<BR><OL>	<LI>Yields; 	<P>	<LI>Quality (including pest damage); 	<P>	<LI>Strategies for soil fertility and crop protection, includingrotational patterns for field- and row-crop farming systems;  		<P>	<LI>Amounts and seasonal timing of pesticide and fertilizer applications. Where available, scientific research and documentation should be referenced, for citation in section IV.	<P></OL><B>B.</B> A summary of technical and financial support for enrolledgrowers, including an outline of the proposed program for outreach andproblem-solving.<P><B>C.</B> A proposed monitoring program to gather the followinginformation at each participating farm: <OL>	<LI> Baseline data documenting the previous years crop yields and quality, fertilizer and pesticide use, and prior usage of elements of BIFS.	<P> 	<LI> In-season data collection to monitor key biological indicators (e.g, pests, biological control agents, and decomposers) and fertilizer and pesticide use.	<P>	<LI> Weather data that are relevant to pest problems.	<P>	<LI> End-of-season crop yield and quality, and pesticide and fertilizer use, and comparison to pre-BIFS data and to county averages.</OL></DL><P>See <A HREF="#Appendix">Appendix</A> for examples from the Merced County Almond BIOS project.Funded projects that do not specify such a monitoring program in theproposal must develop and implement one, in consultation with UC SAREPstaff. <P><B>IV.</B> Literature cited.<P><B>V.</B>Detailed budget, including all sources of support, using thisformat: <P><PRE><B>                                  Matching Funds Category                   Amount    Requested    Source</B>SalariesBenefits Supplies and   Operating Expenses Travel Totals </PRE><B>VI.</B> 	A statement of the applicants accomplishments andqualifications bearing on the success of the project (include resumewith attachments). <P><B>VII.</B> Mandatory attachments, including the letters of intent,memoranda, petitions, and resumes. These must include the following:  <P><DL><B>A.</B>A roster of proposed members of the management team, includingaddresses, and phone numbers, with attachments documenting their experience and achievements in BIFS and signed letters of intent to serve. Each management team must include a project coordinator, at least one BIFS farmer, at least one pest control advisor, a U.C. faculty member, and a U.C. farm advisor or specialist. Any of the technical personnel mentioned can double as project coordinator. The role of management team members is to implement the proposed outreach program and to serve for its duration as resources for participating farmers (see <AHREF="#Appendix">Appendix</A> for additional details).<P><B>B.</B> 	Petition signed by 10-30 farmers of the relevant counties andfarming system, expressing willingness to participate. Participating farmers should represent a range of prior experience with elements of BIFS. However, all participating farmers must be willing to commit acreage as transitional parcels. Acreage may vary according to crop and local farm size. For orchard, vineyard, and field crops, 10-30 acres would be standard. For high-value row crops, lesser acreages may be appropriate. Signatory farmers must agree to implement recommendations to achieve biological integration and agrichemical use reduction, to monitor key variables, and to share data freely with other farmers, the management team, and the community at large. <P><B>C.</B> 	A draft calendar of possible field days for participatingfarmers and the general public (see <A HREF="#Appendix">Appendix</A> for examples).<P><B>D.</B> 	A description of the conventional farming system to beaddressed, specifying and documenting county yields, pest problems, use patterns for pesticides and fertilizers, and any associated environmental, health, or regulatory issues or concerns.<P></DL><B>VIII.</B> Optional attachments. Highest rankings will be assigned toproposals that fulfill the above requirements and also includeattachments documenting the following:<P><DL><B>A.</B> A proposed program ofcontinuing side-by-side comparisons between randomly chosen conventionally managed and BIFS blocks. <P><P><B>B.</B> Expressions of intent (signed letters or memoranda) to providematching contributions, rebates, or cost-sharing from other entities,for example, governmental agencies, academic institutions, non-profitorganizations, commodity groups, and private businesses.<P><B>C.</B> Letters of intent from scientists documenting piggybackresearch projects to be conducted in coordination with the proposed BIFS extension efforts. These projects could involve monitoring selected variables or evaluating proposed improvements to BIFS technology (see <AHREF="#Appendix">Appendix</A> for examples from the Merced County Almond BIOS Project). This criterion is not critical for the first years funding cycle, but will become important in ensuring renewed funding of projects in subsequent years.</DL><P><B>Publications and Annual Reports</B><BR>UC SAREP requires quarterly progress reports and one report at the end of each year of funding. The text format is 10 pt. font, double-spaced. The reports should include the following sections where appropriate: Summary, Introduction, Methods, Results, Discussion, Conclusion, Work Plan for Coming Year, References Cited, Tables, Figures, Attachments (including publications produced by and concerning the funded project). The reports should be provided in hard copy and on floppy diskette.<P><B>Evaluation and Renewal of Funding</B><BR>In total, projects can qualify for up to 3 years of funding. To qualify, a report must be submitted that confirms and documents continued grower participation and progress in agrichemical use reduction and adoption of BIFS practices, while maintaining yields and quality. Data may also be presented on adoption of BIFS technology by non-participating farmers who have been influenced by the outreach program. The report must include an updated work plan for the coming year. As mentioned above, documentation of increasing matching contributions and numbers of piggyback scientific studies will be increasingly important criteria for renewed funding. Evidence of continual enrichment and refinement of BIFS technology will also be an important criterion, as will continuing side-by-side comparisons of BIFS and conventional practices. The reports will be evaluated by the Program Review Advisory Board, with final decisions on renewed funding being made by the Director of UC SAREP.<P><B>Further Information</B><BR>For further information, contact Robert L. Bugg at the above-listedaddress or at 916-754-8549, E-mail <AHREF="mailto:rlbugg@ucdavis.edu">rlbugg@ucdavis.edu</A><P><PRE></PRE><H2><A NAME = "Appendix">Appendix: A Brief Description of BIOSProjects</A></H2> Biologically Integrated Orchard Systems (BIOS)projects, administered by the Community Alliance with Family Farmers Foundation (CAFF Foundation), are intended to assist farmers who wish to increase their knowledge and use of functional farm biology, in order to decrease their reliance on agricultural chemicals. <P>Each of the three previous BIOS projects (in Merced, Stanislaus, and Solano-Yolo Counties) has been conceived as a 3-year voluntary program, with a group of 2030 farmers and their pest control advisors constituting the class of participants.  Interested farmers applied to CAFF Foundation, and a subset of applicants were chosen as participants so as to represent a range of farming practices, soil conditions, locales, and level of experience with biologically integrated farming.  CAFF Foundation assembled a consortium of farmers, U.C. scientists and extension workers, private agricultural consultants, private corporations, and governmental agencies to provide a package of technical and financial support to these participants. <P><B>Technical Support and Evaluation</B><BR>BIOS projects are intended to provide a continually enriched and updated package of technical support, and to evaluate the progress of participating farmers in adopting the suggested techniques and at maintaining yields and quality.  Elements are as follows:<DL><LI> A customized plan for each transitional parcel developed in consultation with the farmer and his or her pest control adviser (PCA) by a "Management Team" of experienced BIOS farmers, a U.C. Cooperative Extension Farm Advisor, and a researcher.<P><LI> A coordinated program of pest monitoring for each parcel, based in part on guidelines from the University of California Statewide Integrated Pest Management (U.C.I.P.M.) Project and developed in consultation with the Management Team and the cooperating PCAs.<P><LI>Customized monitoring program to assess orchard ecology, including cover crop growth, density of earthworms, beneficial arthropods in cover crops in the almond canopy, and pest and beneficial arthropods inside the almonds. <P><LI> Before/after and side-by-side comparison of BIOS and conventional almond orchard blocks.<P><LI> A newsletter summarizing the results of the monitoring and current field conditions sent regularly to participating farmers and PCAs. <P><LI> Consulting services (including a hot line) throughout the season to answer questions concerning the transitional process and to trouble-shoot difficulties that arise.<P><LI> Monthly problem-solving meetings or on-farm workshops, seminars, and facilitated focus sessions.  Topics have included identification and management of pathogens, arthropod pests, beneficial insects, cover crops, resident vegetation, and earthworms; compost quality and use; soil structure as related to cover cropping and soil-borne pathogens; dynamics of soil organic matter; tree nutrition; pruning methods; methods of chipping prunings; owl and bat management; etc.  Upcoming sessions will concern nitrogen cycling in Biologically Integrated Orchard Systems, domestic and wild pollinator insects of almonds, and spray oils, <P><LI> A "BIOS Document" presenting the technical details, scientific background, and trade-offs implicit in the production system.<P><LI> A "BIOS Reader" comprising reprints of technical articles, periodically updated and augmented, supplied to participating farmers and their pest control advisers.<P><LI> Certification credit for pest control advisers and other agricultural consultants who attend BIOS field days and workshops.<P><LI>Evaluation of adoption of BIOS practices by participating farmers. </DL><P><B>Financial Incentives</B><BR>Financial incentives to participating BIOS farmers include thefollowing: <P><DL><LI> Subsidies of up to $20 per acre were available through the U.S.D.A. Consolidated Farm Service SP53 program, administered through the local Resource Conservation District. These subsidies are contingent on the farmer demonstrating a 20% reduction in nitrogen fertilizer or pesticide application.  <P><LI> Cost-sharing and rebates were available through various corporate sponsors for cover crop seed, beneficial insects and mites, insectary shrubs and trees, insect traps, laboratory services, farm implements, and microbial preparations for bioremediation of pre-emergence herbicides.</DL><P><B>A Summary of Features of The BIOS Model</B><BR>The following characteristics of the BIOS model enable comparison to other extension models.  The BIOS model:<P><DL><LI>Addresses farmers directly, as well as pest control advisers and other agricultural consultants.<P><LI>Targets whole production systems.<P><LI>Does not assume a strict top-down, teacher-student relationship whereby specialists impart knowledge to farmers or PCAs.  Rather, the model emphasizes developing a co-learning environment wherein farmers, researchers, and agricultural consultants share insights.<P><LI>External structure is provided by CAFF Foundation.<P><LI>Programmed instruction on a specific type of production system, and the adaptation of the system to individual farms.</DL><BR><B>Piggyback Scientific and Economic Studies</B><BR>The Merced County Almond BIOS Project currently hosts three piggyback scientific studies:<BR><DL><LI>Evaluation of use of nectar-bearing plants by parasitic and predatory insects through rubidium labelling, conducted by Dr. Andrew Corbett of the Department of Entomology, University of California, Davis.<P><LI>Evaluation of the decomposition of cover crop residues and resultant nitrogen mineralization, conducted by Robert McGuinn and Dr. Alison Berry of the Department of Environmental Horticulture,  University of California, Davis. <P><LI>Evaluation of pheromonal confusants for mating disruption of navel orangeworm, conducted by Walt Bentley, Area Advisor with the University of California Statewide Integrated Pest Management Project.<P><LI>Dr. Karen Klonsky of the Department of Agricultural Economics is conducting an economic comparison of BIOS and conventional almond production. </DL><P><B>First-Year Results from Merced County</B><BR>Under BIOS management, first-year survey results, though still incomplete, suggest that most participating Merced County almond growers eliminated organophosphate and pyrethroid dormant sprays, and substantially reduced herbicide and synthetic N fertilizer use.  Data are available for yields and pest damage obtained in ongoing side-by-side comparisons of BIOS and conventionally managed blocks, for before/after comparisons of synthetic N applications, use of pesticides targeted for reduction by the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency, and adoption of BIOS techniques by participating farmers.<P>For further information on the BIOS projects, consult Thomas Nelson,Community Alliance with Family Farmers Foundation, P.O. Box 363, Davis,CA 95617, 916-756-8518, e-mail <A HREF="mailto:caff@igc.apc.org">caff@igc.apc.org</A>
<PRE>

