<html>
<head>
<title>Conference: COMMUNITY FOOD SYSTEMS, Oct. 2-3, 1996</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<IMG src="/Images/sarephdr.gif" alt="SAREP Header Icon" align=left hspace=0><BR clear=all>
<hr>
<center>
<img src="csa96logo.gif" alt="Image: Community food Systems" alt="Image: Farmers Market" width=384 height=172></center>
<h2 align=center>October 2-3, 1996</h2>
<h3 align=center>Buehler Alumni Center<br>
University of California, <br>
Davis, California<br>
</h3>
<p align=center><font size=4><b>For more information, contact:<br>
UC Sustainable Agriculture Research &amp; Education Program <br>
(916) 752-7556<br>
</b></font><b></b></p>
<ul>
<li><a href="#what"><font size=4>What is a Community Food System?</font></a><font size=4> </font></li>
<li><a href="#who"><font size=4>Who Should Attend</font></a><font size=4> </font></li>
<li><a href="#features"><font size=4>Conference Features</font></a><font size=4> </font></li>
<li><a href="#keynote"><font size=4>Keynote Speakers</font></a><font size=4> </font></li>
<li><a href="#Program"><font size=4>Program</font></a><font size=4> </font></li>
<li><a href="#Logistics"><font size=4>Logistics</font></a><font size=4> </font></li>
<li><a href="reg.html"><font size=4>Registration Form</font></a><font size=4> </font></li>
</ul>
<img src="market.gif" align=right hspace=10 vspace=10 width=206 height=285>
<h2><a name="what">What</a> is a Community Food System?</h2>
<p>A community food system is a collaborative effort in a particular place to build more locally-based, self-reliant food economies. 
Community food systems seek comprehensive solutions to food and agricultural problems by involving community members in 
promoting: community food security; farmland preservation; local, direct marketing; community economic development; a stable base 
of family farmers that use production practices that are less chemical and energy-intensive; improved working and living conditions 
for farm labor; and public policies and planning that encourage a more sustainable food system. </p>
<h2><a name="who">Who</a> Should Attend?</h2>
<p>This conference is intended for a diverse audience, including representatives of community-based organizations, Cooperative 
Extension, farmers, University faculty, anti-hunger and food security representatives, farmers' market personnel, consumers, 
community gardeners, economic development planners, local government officials, church groups, environmentalists and others 
interested in developing a more locally-based, self-reliant food system. </p>
<h2>Conference <a name="features">Features</a></h2>
<ul>
<li>Challenging keynote addresses that articulate the role of community food systems in the midst of the global food economy, </li>
<li>Panel presentations of innovative community food system projects from across California, including SAREP-funded projects, </li>
<li>Plenaries that describe coalitions, institutions and businesses that can promote the long-term sustainability of community food 
systems, </li>
<li>Workshops in which to learn and share practical skills for developing community food systems, </li>
<li>Time for networking and building bridges of cooperation among allies, </li>
<li>Social time, food, culture and entertainment at the famous Davis Farmers' Market, and </li>
<li>Delicious lunches prepared from locally grown foods </li>
</ul>
<hr>
<h2><a name="keynote">Keynote</a> Speakers</h2>
<p><b><i>Joan Dye Gussow</i></b> is Mary Swartz Rose Professor emeritus and former chair of the Nutrition Education Program at Teachers 
College, Columbia University. In addition to her teaching duties, Dr. Gussow has served as consultant to various public, private and 
governmental organizations, and has produced several books and a variety of articles on food and nutrition topics. Her latest book, 
Chicken Little, Tomato Sauce and Agriculture was published by Bootstrap Press in 1991. Having advocated relocalizing the food 
supply for 25 years, Joan has recently relocalized herself. Living on the west bank of the Hudson River, in a village called Piermont, 
Gussow co-chairs the Piermont Community Garden, serves on the Piermont Conservation Advisory Committee and is co-chair of 
the Subcommittee on Planning of the Piermont 2000 Committee. As she has for 25 years, she also grows much of her own food with 
the help of her husband, Alan. </p>
<p><b><i>Daniel Kemmis</i></b>, the Mayor of Missoula, is a former speaker of the Montana House of Representatives and was a Montana 
legislator for eight years. He is the author of The Good City and the Good Life and Community and the Politics of Place. A former 
Chair of the National League of Cities Leadership Training Council, Mayor Kemmis is a member of the Board of Directors of the 
National Civic League, the Kettering Foundation and the Pew Partnership for Civic Change. A graduate of Harvard University and 
the University of Montana Law School, Mayor Kemmis has published articles on topics such as city design, community building, and 
regional economies. He was recognized by the Utne Reader in 1995 as one of its &quot;100 Visionaries.&quot; </p>
<p><b><i>Fred Kirschenmann</i></b> was born and raised in south central North Dakota on the Kirschenmann Family Farm which he now 
manages. After earning a doctorate in philosophy from the University of Chicago in 1964, he entered academic life as a teacher and 
administrator, culminating in a position as academic dean at Curry College in Boston, Massachusetts. During his academic studies, he 
earned numerous awards and fellowships, including the Rockefeller Fellowship from the University of Chicago. In 1976, Fred 
returned to the family farm to convert the 3100 acre grain and livestock operation into an organic farm. Fred has been active in 
numerous sustainable and organic agriculture organizations, including Farm Verified Organic, Inc., a private certification agency, the 
USDA National Sustainable Agriculture Advisory Council and the National Organic Standards Board. He has written extensively on 
sustainable agriculture. </p>
<hr>
